[24/06/23, 10:07:05 AM] Satvik Saini: #include<iostream>
using namespace std;
int binomialCoeff(int n, int k);
void Pascal(int n){
    for (int j = 0; j < n; j++){
		for(int i=0;i<=2*(n-j-1);i++){
			cout<<" ";
		}
        for (int i = 0; i <= j; i++){
			cout <<binomialCoeff(j, i)<<"   ";
		}
        	cout <<endl;
    }
}
int binomialCoeff(int n, int k){
    int res = 1;
    if (k > n - k)
    k = n - k;
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++){
        res *= (n - i);
        res /= (i + 1);
    }
    return res;
}
int main(){
    int n;
	cin>>n;
    Pascal(n);
    return 0;
}

[26/06/23, 6:59:30 PM] Satvik Saini: Ruk fir
[26/06/23, 7:08:05 PM] Satvik Saini: Comp notes

ALGORITHM : An algorithm is a sequence of instructions that are carried out in a predetermined sequence in order to solve a problem or complete a work.

FLOWCHART : A flowchart is a diagram that shows an overview of a program . Flowcharts normally use standard symbols to represent the different types of instructions . These symbols are used to construct the flowchart and show the step-by-step solution to the problem.

ASSEMBLY LANGUAGE : Assembly language (or Assembler) is a compiled, low-level computer language. It is processor-dependent, since it basically translates the Assembler's mnemonics directly into the commands a particular CPU understands, on a one-to-one basis.

MEDIUM LEVEL LANGUAGE : Middle-level language is a computer language in which the instructions are created using symbols such as letters, digits and special characters.

HIGH LEVEL LANGUAGE : A high-level language is any programming language that enables development of a program in a much more user-friendly programming context and is generally independent of the computer's hardware architecture

COMPILER : A compiler is a special program that translates a programming language's source code into machine code, bytecode or another programming language.

INTERPRETER : an interpreter is software that examines a computer program one instruction at a time and calls on code to execute the machine operations required by that instruction.

DATA TYPES : data type refers to the type of value a variable has and what type of mathematical, relational or logical operations can be applied without causing an error.

DATA QUANTIFIERS : Quantifiers are used in quantified expressions in which the free variables are bound by the quantifiers. In other words, the variables of the predicates are quantified by quantifiers.

FUNCTION : A function is simply a “block” of code that you can use over and over again, rather than writing it out multiple times. Functions enable programmers to break down or decompose a problem into smaller chunks, each of which performs a particular task.

ARRAYS : An array is a series of memory locations – or 'boxes' – each of which holds a single item of data, but with each box sharing the same name. All data in an array must be of the same data type .

TOKENS :  : A token in C can be defined as the smallest individual element of the C programming language that is meaningful to the compiler. It is the basic component of a C program.A token in C can be defined as the smallest individual element of the C programming language that is meaningful to the compiler. It is the basic component of a C program.

Preprocessor : It is a program that processes our source program before it is passed to the compiler.

Macro : UPPER and PI in the above programs are often called ‘macro templates’, whereas, 25 and 3.1415 are called their corresponding ‘macro expansions’.

Macro VS Function : In a macro call the preprocessor replaces the macro template with its macro expansion, in a stupid, unthinking, literal way. As against this, in a function call the control is passed to a function along with certain arguments, some calculations are performed in the function and a useful value is returned back from the function. Usually macros make the program run faster but increase the program size, whereas functions make the program smaller and compact.


￼

 
STRUCTURE : The structure in C is a user-defined data type that can be used to group items of possibly different types into a single type. The struct keyword is used to define the structure in the C programming language. 

STRING : a string can also be defined as a sequence of characters, stored in contiguous memory locations, terminated by a special character called the null character ‘\0’

2D ARRAY : The two-dimensional array can be defined as an array of arrays. The 2D array is organised as matrices which can be represented as the collection of rows and columns. However, 2D arrays are created to implement a relational database lookalike data structure. It provides ease of holding the bulk of data at once which can be passed to any number of functions wherever required.

POINTERS : It is a variable which stores the address of another variable. This variable can be of type int, char, array, function, or any other pointer. The size of the pointer depends on the architecture.

NULL CHARACTER : The Null character is used to end character strings in the C coding language. In other terms, in C, the Null character represents the conclusion of a string, the end of an array, or other concepts. '0' or '\0' or simply NULL represents the conclusion of the character string or NULL byte.

RECURSION : Recursion is the process which comes into existence when a function calls a copy of itself to work on a smaller problem. Any function which calls itself is called recursive function, and such function calls are called recursive calls.

CLASS : In C++, class is a group of similar objects. It is a template from which objects are created. It can have fields, methods, constructors etc.
 OBJECTS : object is an entity that has state and behaviour. Here, state means data and behaviour means functionality. Object is a runtime entity, it is created at runtime. Object is an instance of a class. All the members of the class can be accessed through object.

￼

Strlen : it is used to find the length of a string. The strlen() function in C returns an integer with the length of the string excluding the NULL character.

strcat : it concatenates string2 to string1 and ends the resulting string with the null character. The strcat() function operates on null-ended strings. The string arguments to the function should contain a null character (\0) that marks the end of the string.

sqrt : it returns the square root of the number. It takes a single parameter         (in double) and returns the output as a double. It returns a domain error if the input is negative.

DMA and Function available in DMA : This concept  enables the C programmer to allocate memory at runtime. Dynamic memory allocation in c language is possible by 4 functions of stdlib.h header file.
1. malloc()
2. calloc()
3. realloc()
4. free()

￼

FILE HANDLING : It enables us to create, update, read, and delete the files stored on the local file system through our C program. The following operations can be performed on a file.
* Creation of the new file
* Opening an existing file
* Reading from the file
* Writing to the file
* Deleting the file

 CONTROL STATEMENTS : hey allow programmers to control the flow of execution of their programs. In C, there are three types of control statements: 
* selection statements
* iteration statements
* jump statements.


PREPROCESSOR : It is a program that processes our source program before it is passed to the compiler.

MACRO : UPPER and PI in the above programs are often called ‘macro templates’, whereas, 25 and 3.1415 are called their corresponding ‘macro expansions’.

MACRO VS FUNCTION : In a macro call the preprocessor replaces the macro template with its macro expansion, in a stupid, unthinking, literal way. As against this, in a function call the control is passed to a function along with certain arguments, some calculations are performed in the function and a useful value is returned back from the function. Usually macros make the program run faster but increase the program size, whereas functions make the program smaller and compact.

PILLARS OF OOPS : 

- INHERITANCE : When one object acquires all the properties and behaviours of parent object i.e. known as inheritance. It provides code reusability. 
    * Single
    * Multi-level
    * Multiple
    * Hierarchical
    * Hybrid

- POLYMORPHISM : 

- ENCAPSULATION :Binding (or wrapping) code and data together into a single unit

- ABSTRACTION : Hiding internal details and showing functionality is known as abstraction. Data abstraction is the process of exposing to the outside world only the information that is absolutely ne
- necessary while concealing implementation or background information.

FUNCTION OVERLOADING : Function Overloading is defined as the process of having two or more function with the same name, but different in parameters is known as function overloading in C++. In function overloading, the function is redefined by using either different types of arguments or a different number of arguments.

FUNCTION OVERRIDING : If derived class defines same function as defined in its base class, it is known as function overriding in C++. It is used to achieve runtime polymorphism. It enables you to provide specific implementation of the function which is already provided by its base class.

[29/06/23, 11:05:18 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: how to create pointer to array ? use pointer to input data to array in c
[29/06/23, 11:05:24 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <stdio.h>

#define ARRAY_SIZE 5

int main() {
  int array[ARRAY_SIZE];
  int (*ptr)[ARRAY_SIZE] = &array;

  printf("Enter %d integers:\n", ARRAY_SIZE);

  // Input data into array using pointer
  for (int i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE; i++) {
    scanf("%d", (*ptr)[i]);
  }

  printf("Array elements:\n");

  // Output array elements using pointer
  for (int i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE; i++) {
    printf("%d ", (*ptr)[i]);
  }

  return 0;
}

[01/07/23, 9:05:35 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: Moving iron type measuring instruments are a class of electromechanical instruments used for measuring electrical quantities such as voltage, current, and power. These instruments operate based on the principle of the interaction between a magnetic field and a movable iron piece.

Here are some key points about moving iron type measuring instruments:

1. Working Principle: The basic working principle involves a movable iron piece, known as the moving element, which is attracted towards or repelled from a stationary iron piece when a current flows through a coil or winding. The force between the magnetic field generated by the coil and the iron piece causes the movement, which is then calibrated to indicate the measured quantity.

2. Construction: Moving iron instruments typically consist of a coil or winding arrangement and a movable iron vane or pointer. The coil is wound on a soft iron core, and the movable iron vane is attached to a spindle or pivot. As the current flows through the coil, it generates a magnetic field, which interacts with the movable iron vane, causing it to move.

3. Types of Moving Iron Instruments: There are two primary types of moving iron instruments:
   a. Attraction Type: In this type, the movable iron piece is attracted towards the coil when current flows through it. The deflection of the pointer is proportional to the square of the current.
   b. Repulsion Type: In this type, the movable iron piece is repelled from the coil when current flows through it. The deflection of the pointer is directly proportional to the current.

4. Applications: Moving iron instruments are commonly used for AC and DC measurements in various electrical systems. They are suitable for measuring both high and low currents and voltages. These instruments find applications in power distribution systems, laboratories, industrial settings, and electrical testing and measurement.

5. Advantages and Limitations: Moving iron instruments have the following advantages:
   - Wide measurement range and good sensitivity.
   - Can measure both AC and DC quantities.
   - Robust construction and relatively low cost.

   However, they also have some limitations:
   - Non-linear scale due to the square or linear relationship with the measured quantity.
   - Relatively slower response compared to some other instrument types.
   - Susceptible to errors caused by external magnetic fields.

Overall, moving iron type measuring instruments are widely used in electrical measurements due to their versatility, robustness, and suitability for a wide range of current and voltage measurements.

[01/07/23, 9:16:51 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: PMMC Instruments for DC: PMMC instruments are specifically designed for DC (Direct Current) measurements. They operate based on the principle of a permanent magnet and a moving coil. When a current flows through the coil, it generates a magnetic field that interacts with the magnetic field of the permanent magnet, causing a torque and deflection of the coil. PMMC instruments offer good accuracy, sensitivity, and linearity for DC measurements.

Moving Coil Instruments for AC and DC: Moving Coil instruments, also known as dynamometer type instruments, are capable of measuring both AC (Alternating Current) and DC quantities. They utilize a moving coil and a fixed magnetic field. The coil is suspended in the magnetic field and experiences a torque proportional to the current flowing through it, regardless of whether it is AC or DC. The instrument's design allows it to respond to the average value of the current or voltage, making it suitable for measuring both types of currents.

The key difference between PMMC and Moving Coil instruments lies in their construction and sensitivity to the type of current being measured. PMMC instruments are optimized for DC measurements and provide precise readings for such applications. On the other hand, Moving Coil instruments are more versatile and can handle both AC and DC measurements, although their accuracy might be affected by factors like frequency and waveform distortion in AC measurements.

[01/07/23, 9:34:32 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: Dynamometer type measuring instruments, also known as moving coil instruments or electrodynamometer instruments, are a class of electromechanical measuring instruments used for measuring electrical quantities such as current, voltage, power, and energy. They operate based on the interaction between magnetic fields and the current flowing through a coil.

Here are some key points about dynamometer type measuring instruments:

Working Principle: Dynamometer instruments use the principle of the interaction between the magnetic field produced by a fixed coil and the magnetic field produced by a movable coil. When a current flows through the movable coil, it generates a magnetic field that interacts with the fixed coil's magnetic field, resulting in a torque that causes the coil to move. The movement is calibrated to indicate the measured quantity.

Construction: Dynamometer instruments typically consist of a fixed coil, a movable coil suspended within the magnetic field of the fixed coil, and a pointer attached to the movable coil. The movable coil is usually wound with a few turns of thick wire, while the fixed coil has a large number of turns of fine wire. This design allows for greater sensitivity and accuracy.

Types of Dynamometer Instruments: There are two main types of dynamometer instruments:
a. Attraction Type: In this type, the movable coil is attracted towards the fixed coil when a current flows through it. The deflection of the pointer is proportional to the square of the current or voltage being measured.
b. Repulsion Type: In this type, the movable coil is repelled from the fixed coil when a current flows through it. The deflection of the pointer is directly proportional to the current or voltage being measured.

Applications: Dynamometer instruments are commonly used for accurate measurements in AC and DC electrical systems. They are suitable for measuring both high and low currents and voltages, making them versatile instruments. These instruments find applications in power distribution systems, laboratories, industrial settings, electrical testing and measurement, and watt-hour metering.

Advantages and Limitations: Dynamometer type measuring instruments offer several advantages:

Good accuracy, sensitivity, and linearity.
Wide measurement range for both AC and DC quantities.
Suitable for power and energy measurements.
However, they also have some limitations:

Relatively higher cost compared to other types of measuring instruments.
Susceptible to errors caused by external magnetic fields.
Require calibration and periodic maintenance.
Overall, dynamometer type measuring instruments are widely used in electrical measurements due to their accuracy, versatility, and suitability for a wide range of current, voltage, power, and energy measurements.

[05/07/23, 5:50:49 PM] Satvik Saini: ASCII : (American Standard Code for Information Interchange)

ANSI : American National Standards Institute

ALGORITHM : An algorithm is a sequence of instructions that are carried out in a predetermined sequence in order to solve a problem or complete a work.

FLOWCHART : A flowchart is a diagram that shows an overview of a program . Flowcharts normally use standard symbols to represent the different types of instructions . These symbols are used to construct the flowchart and show the step-by-step solution to the problem.

ASSEMBLY LANGUAGE : Assembly language (or Assembler) is a compiled, low-level computer language. It is processor-dependent, since it basically translates the Assembler's mnemonics directly into the commands a particular CPU understands, on a one-to-one basis.

MEDIUM LEVEL LANGUAGE : Middle-level language is a computer language in which the instructions are created using symbols such as letters, digits and special characters.

HIGH LEVEL LANGUAGE : A high-level language is any programming language that enables development of a program in a much more user-friendly programming context and is generally independent of the computer's hardware architecture

COMPILER : A compiler is a special program that translates a programming language's source code into machine code, bytecode or another programming language.

INTERPRETER : an interpreter is software that examines a computer program one instruction at a time and calls on code to execute the machine operations required by that instruction.

DATA TYPES : data type refers to the type of value a variable has and what type of mathematical, relational or logical operations can be applied without causing an error.

DATA QUANTIFIERS : Quantifiers are used in quantified expressions in which the free variables are bound by the quantifiers. In other words, the variables of the predicates are quantified by quantifiers.

FUNCTION : A function is simply a “block” of code that you can use over and over again, rather than writing it out multiple times. Functions enable programmers to break down or decompose a problem into smaller chunks, each of which performs a particular task.

ARRAYS : An array is a series of memory locations – or 'boxes' – each of which holds a single item of data, but with each box sharing the same name. All data in an array must be of the same data type .

TOKENS :  A token in C can be defined as the smallest individual element of the C programming language that is meaningful to the compiler. It is the basic component of a C program.

Preprocessor : It is a program that processes our source program before it is passed to the compiler.

Macro : Macro in c is defined by the #define directive. Macro is a name given to a piece of code, so whenever the compiler encounters a macro in a program, it will replace it with the macro value. In the macro definition, the macros are not terminated by the semicolon(;)
[05/07/23, 5:51:05 PM] Satvik Saini: STRUCTURE : The structure in C is a user-defined data type that can be used to group items of possibly different types into a single type. The struct keyword is used to define the structure in the C programming language. 
￼


STRING : a string can also be defined as a sequence of characters, stored in contiguous memory locations, terminated by a special character called the null character ‘\0’

2D ARRAY : The two-dimensional array can be defined as an array of arrays. The 2D array is organised as matrices which can be represented as the collection of rows and columns. However, 2D arrays are created to implement a relational database lookalike data structure. It provides ease of holding the bulk of data at once which can be passed to any number of functions wherever required.

POINTERS : It is a variable which stores the address of another variable. This variable can be of type int, char, array, function, or any other pointer. The size of the pointer depends on the architecture.

NULL CHARACTER : The Null character is used to end character strings in the C coding language. In other terms, in C, the Null character represents the conclusion of a string, the end of an array, or other concepts. '0' or '\0' or simply NULL represents the conclusion of the character string or NULL byte.

RECURSION : Recursion is the process which comes into existence when a function calls a copy of itself to work on a smaller problem. Any function which calls itself is called recursive function, and such function calls are called recursive calls.

CLASS : In C++, class is a group of similar objects. It is a template from which objects are created. It can have fields, methods, constructors etc.
 OBJECTS : object is an entity that has state and behaviour. Here, state means data and behaviour means functionality. Object is a runtime entity, it is created at runtime. Object is an instance of a class. All the members of the class can be accessed through object.

￼

Strlen : it is used to find the length of a string. The strlen() function in C returns an integer with the length of the string excluding the NULL character.

strcat : it concatenates string2 to string1 and ends the resulting string with the null character. The strcat() function operates on null-ended strings. The string arguments to the function should contain a null character (\0) that marks the end of the string.

sqrt : it returns the square root of the number. It takes a single parameter         (in double) and returns the output as a double. It returns a domain error if the input is negative.

DMA and Function available in DMA : This concept  enables the C programmer to allocate memory at runtime. Dynamic memory allocation in c language is possible by 4 functions of stdlib.h header file.
1. malloc()
2. calloc()
3. realloc()
4. free()
[05/07/23, 5:51:16 PM] Satvik Saini: FILE HANDLING : It enables us to create, update, read, and delete the files stored on the local file system through our C program. The following operations can be performed on a file.
* Creation of the new file
* Opening an existing file
* Reading from the file
* Writing to the file
* Deleting the file

 CONTROL STATEMENTS : they allow programmers to control the flow of execution of their programs. In C, there are three types of control statements: 
* selection statements
* iteration statements
* jump statements.

PILLARS OF OOPS : 

- INHERITANCE : When one object acquires all the properties and behaviours of parent object i.e. known as inheritance. It provides code reusability. 
    * Single
    * Multi-level
    * Multiple
    * Hierarchical
    * Hybrid

- POLYMORPHISM : 

- ENCAPSULATION :Binding (or wrapping) code and data together into a single unit

- ABSTRACTION : Hiding internal details and showing functionality is known as abstraction. Data abstraction is the process of exposing to the outside world only the information that is absolutely ne
- necessary while concealing implementation or background information.

FUNCTION OVERLOADING : Function Overloading is defined as the process of having two or more function with the same name, but different in parameters is known as function overloading in C++. In function overloading, the function is redefined by using either different types of arguments or a different number of arguments.

FUNCTION OVERRIDING : If derived class defines same function as defined in its base class, it is known as function overriding in C++. It is used to achieve runtime polymorphism. It enables you to provide specific implementation of the function which is already provided by its base class.

[06/07/23, 9:00:32 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: Macros and functions serve similar purposes in C programming, but they have some key differences in terms of their behavior and usage:

1. Expansion Mechanism:
   - Macros: Macros are expanded by the preprocessor as text substitutions. When a macro is encountered in the code, the preprocessor replaces it with its corresponding definition. Macros are expanded before the actual compilation of the code.
   - Functions: Functions are separate blocks of code that are defined and called during the execution of the program. Function calls involve a jump to the function code, execution of the statements inside the function, and a return back to the calling code.

2. Execution Time:
   - Macros: Macros are expanded at the preprocessing stage and are part of the generated code. They do not involve function call overhead and are generally faster at runtime.
   - Functions: Functions are executed during program execution. When a function is called, control is transferred to the function code, which executes the statements inside the function. Functions introduce function call overhead due to stack frame creation, parameter passing, and return value handling.

3. Arguments Evaluation:
   - Macros: Macro arguments are not evaluated in the same way as function arguments. Macro arguments are replaced as text before the macro expansion, which can have unintended side effects. Macros can have unexpected behavior when arguments involve complex expressions or have side effects.
   - Functions: Function arguments are evaluated before the function is called. The expressions passed as function arguments are evaluated exactly once, and the resulting values are used within the function.

4. Scope and Name Space:
   - Macros: Macros are expanded wherever they are encountered in the code. They do not have their own scope or name space. Macros are not limited by the rules of block scope and can be used anywhere in the program.
   - Functions: Functions have their own scope and name space. Function names and variables declared within a function are limited to the scope of that function and are not accessible outside it.

5. Debugging and Code Readability:
   - Macros: Macros can sometimes make debugging more challenging. Since macros are expanded before compilation, debugging tools often show the expanded macro code instead of the original macro definition. Macros can also make code less readable if they are used excessively or if their expansion leads to complex or cryptic code.
   - Functions: Functions make debugging easier as they can be stepped into, stepped over, and examined using debugging tools. Functions can also improve code readability by encapsulating a specific task or functionality into a named block of code.

Generally, it is recommended to use functions over macros unless there is a specific need for macros, such as performance optimization or compile-time customization. Functions offer better code organization, scoping, type checking, and debugging capabilities.

[11/07/23, 6:04:09 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int threeSumClosest(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int ans=INT_MAX,mini = ans;
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        int n = nums.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            int l = i+1,r = n-1;
            
            while(l<r){   
                if(target == nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l]) return target;
                if(target>nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l]){
                    int temp = ans;
                    ans = min(ans,target-(nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l]));
                    if(ans!=temp) mini = nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l];
                    r--;
                }
                else{
                    int temp = ans;
                    ans = min(ans,nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l]-target);
                    if(ans!=temp) mini = nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l];
                    l++;
                }
            }  
        }
        return mini;
    }
};
[11/07/23, 6:04:17 PM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/3sum-closest/
[11/07/23, 6:43:08 PM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/next-permutation/
[11/07/23, 6:43:13 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    void nextPermutation(vector<int>& nums) {
        int c=0;
        int n =nums.size();
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            if(nums[i]<nums[i-1]) c++;
        }
        if(c==n-1){
            sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
            return;
        }
        int swap_idx = 0;
        for(int i=n-1;i>0;i--){
            if(nums[i-1]<nums[i]){
                swap_idx = i-1;
                break;
            }
        }
        int just_greater=0,diff = INT_MAX;
        for(int i=swap_idx+1;i<n;i++){
            if(nums[i]>nums[swap_idx]){
               int temp = diff;
               diff = min(diff,nums[i] - nums[swap_idx]);
               if(temp!=diff) just_greater = i;
            }
        }
        swap(nums[just_greater],nums[swap_idx]);
        return;
        
    }
};
[11/07/23, 7:21:09 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public: 
    int minfromiton(vector<int>& arr,int i,int n){
        int mini = INT_MAX;
        for(int j=i ; j<n ; j++){
            mini = min(arr[i],mini);
        }
        return mini;

    }
    void nextPermutation(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        int i=n-2;
        // for(int j=n-1 ; j<n ; j++)
        while(arr[i]>arr[i+1]){
            i--;
        }
        swap(arr[i],minfromiton(arr,i,n));
        sort(arr+i+1,arr+n);
        return ;
    
    }
};

[11/07/23, 7:50:50 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int maxProduct(vector<int>& nums) {
        int ans=nums[0];
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            for(int j=i;j<nums.size()-i;j++){
                int prod = 1;
                for(int k=i;k<=j;k++){
                    prod *= nums[k];
                }
                ans = max(ans,prod);
            }
        }
    return ans;
    }
};

[12/07/23, 12:47:02 PM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/single-element-in-a-sorted-array/
[12/07/23, 12:47:16 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
// same even no or different odd length
    int singleNonDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        int s=0;
        int e=nums.size();
        if(e==1){
            return nums[0];
        }
        
        while(s<=e){
            int mid=(s+e)/2;
            if(nums[mid]!=nums[mid-1] && nums[mid]!=nums[mid+1]){
                return nums[mid];
            }
            else if(nums[mid]==nums[mid+1]){
                int rc=e-mid+1;
                if(rc%2!=0){
                    e=mid-1;
                }
                else{
                    // s=mid+2;
                    s=mid+1;
                }
            }
            else if(nums[mid]==nums[mid-1]){
                int lc=mid-s+1;
                if(lc%2==0){
                    // e=mid-2;
                    e=mid-1;
                }
                else{
                    s=mid+1;
                }
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};

[12/07/23, 1:29:04 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
// same even no or different odd length
    int singleNonDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        int s=0;
        int e=nums.size()-1;
        //if(e==0){
        //    return nums[0];
        //}
        //if(nums[0]!=nums[1]) return nums[0];
        //if(nums[e-1]!=nums[e]) return nums[e];

        while(s<=e){
            int mid=(s+e)/2;
            if(nums[mid]!=nums[mid-1] && nums[mid]!=nums[mid+1]){
                return nums[mid];
            }
            else if(nums[mid]==nums[mid+1]){
                int rc=e-mid;
                if(rc%2!=0){
                    e=mid-1;
                }
                else{
                    // s=mid+2;
                    s=mid+1;
                }
            }
            else if(nums[mid]==nums[mid-1]){
                int lc=mid-s;
                if(lc%2==0){
                    // e=mid-2;
                    e=mid;
                }
                else{
                    s=mid+1;
                }
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};

[12/07/23, 2:33:20 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findPeakGrid(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int n = mat.size();
        int m = mat[0].size();
        int s = 0;
        int e = m-1;
        vector<int> ans;
        while(s<=e){
            int mid = (s+e)/2;
            int max_idx=0;
            for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
                if(mat[i][mid]>mat[max_idx][mid]){
                    max_idx = i;
                }
            }
            if(mid!=0 && mat[max_idx][mid]<mat[max_idx][mid-1]){
                e = mid-1;
            }
            else if (mid!=m-1 && mat[max_idx][mid]<mat[max_idx][mid+1]){
                s = mid+1;
            }
            else{
                ans.push_back(max_idx);
                ans.push_back(mid);
                return ans;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
[12/07/23, 3:27:46 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int findKthPositive(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
        vector<int> ans;
        int prev = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<arr.size();i++){
            if(arr[i]-prev>1){
                while(arr[i]-prev!=1){
                    ans.push_back(prev+1);
                    prev++;
                }
            }
            prev = arr[i];
        }
        for(int i=arr[arr.size()-1]+1;i<=1000-arr.size();i++){
            ans.push_back(i);
        }
        return ans[k-1];
    }
};

[12/07/23, 6:16:06 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    int no_of_partition(vector<int> arr,int mid){
        int count = 1;
        int sum=0;
        for(int i=0;i<arr.size();i++){
            sum+=arr[i];
            if(sum>mid){
                count++;
                sum = arr[i];
            }
        }
        // int i=0;
        // while(i<arr.size()){
        //     sum+=arr[i];
        //     if(sum>mid){
        //         count++;
        //         sum = 0;
        //         continue;
        //     }
        //     i++;
        // }
        return count;
    }

    int splitArray(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int ans;
        int s=0,e=0;
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            e+=nums[i];
        }
        while(s<=e){
            int mid = e+(s-e)/2;
            int x = no_of_partition(nums,mid);
            if(x<=k) {
                ans = mid;
                e = mid-1;
            }
            else s = mid+1;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

public:
    bool searchMatrix(vector<vector<int>>& arr, int target) {
        int m = sizeof(arr)/sizeof(arr[0]);
        int n = sizeof(arr[0])/sizeof(int);
        int s = 0;
        int e = m-1;
        int ans_row;
        while(s<=e){
            int mid = (s+e)/2;
            if(arr[mid][n-1] == target)  return true;
            else if(target>arr[mid][n-1]){
                s = mid+1;
            }
            else{
                ans_row = mid;
                e = mid-1;
            }

        }
        return  binary_search(arr[ans_row].begin(),arr[ans_row].end(),target);
            
        
        
    }
};

public:
    bool searchMatrix(vector<vector<int>>& arr, int target) {
        int m = sizeof(arr)/sizeof(arr[0]);
        int n = sizeof(arr[0])/sizeof(int);
        int s = 0;
        int e = m-1;
        int ans_row = -1;
        while(s<=e){
            int mid = (s+e)/2;
            if(arr[mid][n-1] == target)  return true;
            else if(target>arr[mid][n-1]){
                s = mid+1;
            }
            else{
                ans_row = mid;
                e = mid-1;
            }

        }
        if(ans_row == -1) return false;
        return  binary_search(arr[ans_row].begin(),arr[ans_row].end(),target);
            
        
        
    }

[14/07/23, 8:59:38 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findPeakGrid(vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int n = mat.size(), m = mat[0].size();
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while(1){

        e.g.// [1,2,3,4,5,6, 7, 8 ]
            // [2,3,4,5,6,7, 8, 9 ]
            // [3,4,5,6,7,8, 9, 10]
            // [4,5,6,7,8,9, 10 11]

            int ele = mat[i][j];
            int left = j - 1 >= 0 ? mat[i][j - 1] : -1;
            int right = j + 1 < m ? mat[i][j + 1] : - 1;
            int up = i - 1 >= 0 ? mat[i - 1][j] : -1;
            int down = i + 1 < n ? mat[i + 1][j] : - 1;

            //set ele to max 
            if(ele < left) ele = left;  
            if(ele < right) ele = right; //fall through
            if(ele < up) ele = up;      //fall through
            if(ele < down) ele = down; //fall through

            //check in which direction we got the max element
            if(ele == left) j --;
            else if(ele == right) j ++;
            else if(ele == up) i --;
            else if(ele == down) i ++;
            else return {i, j}; //if mat[i][j] is itself peak element
        }
    }
};
[14/07/23, 9:06:48 AM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/partition-array-into-disjoint-intervals/
[14/07/23, 9:07:03 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int partitionDisjoint(vector<int>& nums) {
        if(nums.size()==2 && nums[0]==nums[1]) return 1;
        int prev_p=-1;
        int ele = nums[0];

        for(int i=nums.size()-1;i>=0;i--){
            if(nums[i]<ele){
                prev_p = i+1;
                break;
            }
        }
        if(prev_p==-1) return 1;
        int curr_p;

        for(int i=1;i<prev_p;i++){
            ele = nums[i];
            for(int j=nums.size()-1;j>=0;j--){
                if(nums[j]<ele){
                    curr_p = j+1;
                    if(curr_p>prev_p){
                        prev_p = curr_p;
                    }
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        return prev_p;
        
    }
};

void replacepi(string out , string inp ){
    
    // base case
    if(inp.empty())  {
        return ;
    }

    //recursive case

    //if i get my first two as pi then put 3.14 in my output array and calculate for the remaining string

    if(inp[0] == 'p' and inp[1] == 'i'){
        out = out + "3.14";
        
        replacepi(out,inp.substr(2));
        
    }
    out = out + inp[0];
    replacepi(out,inp.substr(1));
     // if i do not get pi in first two then put first character in output array and ask your freind to calculate the ramiang string 
}

int main(){
    string inp = "pipipipijbsdppp";
    string out = "";
    replacepi(out,inp);
    cout<<out<<endl;

    return 0;
}

using namespace std;
long int changeto5(int n){

	//base case
	if(n==0){
		return 0;
	}


	//recursive case
	int lastnum = n%10;
	if(lastnum==5){
		// long int frnd_ans = ;
		return changeto5(n/10)*10;
	}
	else{
		return 10*changeto5(n/10) + lastnum;
	}
}
int main () {
	long int n;
	cin>>n;
	cout<<changeto5(n)<<endl;
	return 0;
}

using namespace std;
int counttwins(string str  ){
	
	//base case
	if(str.empty()) {
		return 0;
	}

	//recusrsive case
	
	char twinchar = str[0];
	if(str[1] == 'X' and str[2] == twinchar){
		return counttwins(str.substr(2)) + 1 ;
	}
	return counttwins(str.substr(2));
}

[16/07/23, 2:44:00 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include<iostream>
using namespace std;
int firstocc(int* arr, int target, int n){
    int s =0;
    int e=n-1;
    int ans = -1;
    while(s<=e){
        int mid = (s+e)/2;
        if(arr[mid] == target){
            ans = mid;
            e = mid -1;

        }
        else if(arr[mid]>target){
            e = mid-1;
        }
        else{
            s = mid+1;
        }
    }
    return ans;

}
int lastocc(int* arr, int target,int n){
    int s =0;
    int e=n-1;
    int ans = -1;
    while(s<=e){
        int mid = (s+e)/2;
        if(arr[mid] == target){
            ans = mid;
            s = mid +1;

        }
        else if(arr[mid]>target){
            e = mid-1;
        }
        else{
            s = mid+1;
        }
    }
    return ans;

}

int main() {
    int n, x;
    cin >> n;
    int arr[n];
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> arr[i];
    }
    cin >> x;
    firstocc(arr,x,n) == -1 ? cout<<0 :   cout << lastocc(arr,x,n)-firstocc(arr, x,n) + 1;
}

[16/07/23, 6:21:37 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include<iostream>
using namespace std;
int count = 0;
void f(char* inp , int i){

    //base case
    if(inp[i] == '\0'){
       count ++;
        return ;
    }


    //recursive case
    int n = strlen(inp);
    for(int j = i ; j<n ; j++){
        bool flag = true;

          for(int k = j+1 ; k<n ; k++){
            if(inp[k] == inp[j]){
                flag = false;
                break;
            }
          }
          if(flag){
            swap(inp[i],inp[j]);
            f(inp,i+1);
            swap(inp[i],inp[j]);
          }
        
    }


}
int main(){
    char inp[] = "satvik==bc";
    // char out[100];
    f(inp,0);
   cout<<count<<endl;
    return 0;
}

using namespace std;
string keypad[] = {"","","abc","def","ghi","jkl","mno","pqrs","tuv","wxyz"};
void f(char* inp, char* out, int i,int j){
    //base case
    if(inp[i] == '\0'){
        out[j] = '\0';
        cout<<out<<endl;
        return;
    }
    //recursive case
    int d = inp[i] - '0';
    string optionstring = keypad[d];

    for(int k = 0 ; k<optionstring.size() ; k++){
            out[j] = optionstring[k];
             f(inp,out,i+1,j+1);
    }
}

    return 0;

[18/07/23, 8:10:07 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include<iostream>
using namespace std;
bool check(string str,int i,int n){
	//base case 
	if(i==n){
		return true;
	}
	//recursive case

	if(str[i]=='a'){
		if(i==0 || str[i-1] == 'a'){
			return check(str,i+1,n);
		}
		else if(str[i-1] == 'b' and str[i-2]=='b')  return check(str,i+1,n);
		else{
			return false;
		}
	}
	else if(str[i] == 'b' and str[i+1] == 'b'){
			if(i==0 || str[i-1] == 'a') return check(str,i+2,n);
			else{
				return false;
			}
		}
		if(i==0){
			return false;
		}
		return check(str,i+1,n);


	
}

[19/07/23, 6:38:06 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int threeSumClosest(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int ans=INT_MAX,mini = ans;
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        int n = nums.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            int l = i+1,r = n-1;

            while(l<r){   
                if(target == nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l]) return target;
                if(target>nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l]){
                    int temp = ans;
                    ans = min(ans,target-(nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l]));
                    if(ans!=temp) mini = nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l];
                    l++;
                }
                else{
                    int temp = ans;
                    ans = min(ans,nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l]-target);
                    if(ans!=temp) mini = nums[i]+nums[r]+nums[l];
                    r--;
                }
            }  
        }
        return mini;
    }
};
[19/07/23, 6:46:07 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int maxProduct(vector<int>& nums) {
        int ans=nums[0];
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            for(int j=i;j<nums.size();j++){
                int prod = 1;
                for(int k=i;k<=j;k++){
                    prod *= nums[k];
                }
                ans = max(ans,prod);
            }
        }
    return ans;
    }
};

        int ans = INT_MIN;

        int n = nums.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(prefix == 0) prefix = 1;
            if(suffix == 0) suffix = 1;

    {
        int ans=arr[0],prefix=1,sfix = 1;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            prefix*= arr[i];
            sfix*=arr[n-i-1];
            if(sfix<1)
            sfix=1;
            if(prefix<1)
            prefix=1;
            int t = Math.max(prefix,sfix);
            ans = Math.max(ans,t);
        }
        return ans;
    }
[19/07/23, 8:12:25 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    int maxProduct(vector<int>& nums) {
       int maxi=INT_MIN,prefix=1,suffix=1;
       for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
           if(prefix==0) prefix=1;
               if(suffix==0) suffix=1;
               
           prefix=prefix*nums[i];
           suffix=suffix*nums[nums.size()-i-1];
           maxi=max(maxi,max(prefix,suffix));
       }
       return maxi;
    }
};
[19/07/23, 8:12:52 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
    public int maxProduct(int[] nums) {
        if(nums.length == 1){
            return nums[0];
        }
       int leftHighestCount = 0;
       int leftTempCounter = 1;
       int rightHighestCount = 0;
       int rightTempCounter = 1;
       for(int i =0; i< nums.length; i++)
        {
           if(nums[i] == 0 )
           {
               if( nums[i] > leftHighestCount)
               {
                  leftHighestCount = nums[i];
               }
              leftTempCounter = 1 ;
           } else {
            leftTempCounter = nums[i] * leftTempCounter;
           
             if(leftTempCounter > leftHighestCount)
           {
              leftHighestCount = leftTempCounter;
           }
           }
          
          
       }

        for(int i = nums.length - 1 ; i >= 0; i--)
        {
            if(nums[i] == 0 )
           {
                if( nums[i] > rightHighestCount)
               {
                  rightHighestCount = nums[i];
               }
              rightTempCounter = 1 ;
           } else {
            rightTempCounter = nums[i] * rightTempCounter;
    
             if(rightTempCounter > rightHighestCount)
           {
              rightHighestCount = rightTempCounter;
           }
           }
        }
        System.out.print(rightHighestCount);
        System.out.print(leftHighestCount);
       if(rightHighestCount > leftHighestCount)
       {
           return rightHighestCount;
       }

       return leftHighestCount;
       
    }
}
[19/07/23, 8:13:50 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    int maxProduct(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int>v(nums.size(),0);
        int odd=0,oval;
        int till=1,ans=nums[0];
        v[0]=nums[0];
        if(nums[0]<0){
            oval=0;
            odd+=1;
        }
        for(int i=1;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(nums[i]>0){
                if(v[i-1]<0)
                    v[i]=nums[i];
                else if(!v[i-1])
                    v[i]=nums[i];
                else
                    v[i]=nums[i]*v[i-1];
            }
            else if(nums[i]<0){
                if(v[i-1])
                    v[i]=v[i-1]*nums[i];
                else
                    v[i]=nums[i];
                odd+=1;
                if(odd==1)
                    oval=i;
                else{
                    if(odd%2 ==0){
                        if(oval==i-1)
                            continue;
                        v[i]*=v[oval];
                    }
                    else{
                        v[i]/=v[oval];
                    }
                }
            }
            else{
                v[i]=0;
                odd=0;
            }
        }
        for(int x:v)
            ans=max(ans,x);
        return ans;
        
    }
};
[19/07/23, 8:14:13 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: Here main thing to notice is that first negative number is important, we need to save location of that number and multiply when negative number is even and divide when negative number is odd.\
[19/07/23, 8:15:41 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: The code works correctly because it considers both the prefix and suffix products to handle cases where the subarray with the maximum product may start or end at any index within the array. The prefix product keeps track of the product of elements from the beginning of the array to the current index, and the suffix product keeps track of the product of elements from the end of the array to the current index. This way, the algorithm covers all possible contiguous subarrays and finds the one with the maximum product.
[19/07/23, 8:19:23 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: Certainly! Let's explain the code in simpler terms:

The goal of the code is to find the maximum product of a continuous subarray within the given array `nums`. The subarray can start and end at any position within the array.

The code uses two variables, `prefix` and `suffix`, to keep track of the product of elements in the subarray as it progresses through the array. 

Here's how it works step by step:

1. Initialize `maxi` (the maximum product found so far) to a very small value, so any positive value in the array will update it.

2. Loop through each element in the array.

3. At each step, update the `prefix` by multiplying it with the current element (`nums[i]`). The `prefix` now represents the product of the subarray starting from the beginning and ending at the current index.

4. Similarly, update the `suffix` by multiplying it with the element at the corresponding position from the end of the array (`nums[nums.size()-i-1]`). The `suffix` now represents the product of the subarray starting from the end and ending at the current index.

5. Keep track of the maximum product found so far (`maxi`). Compare `maxi`, `prefix`, and `suffix`, and update `maxi` to the maximum value among these three variables.

6. Continue the loop until all elements in the array have been processed.

7. After the loop ends, the `maxi` variable contains the maximum product of a contiguous subarray within the given array.

By considering both the `prefix` and `suffix` products, the code ensures that it covers all possible contiguous subarrays and finds the one with the maximum product. This approach helps handle cases where the subarray with the maximum product may start or end at any index within the array.

[20/07/23, 9:09:49 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int findKthPositive(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
        vector<int> ans;
        int prev = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<arr.size();i++){
            if(arr[i]-prev>1){
                while(arr[i]-prev!=1){
                    ans.push_back(prev+1);
                    prev++;
                }
            }
            prev = arr[i];
        }
        for(int i=arr[arr.size()-1]+1;i<=1000-arr.size();i++){
            ans.push_back(i);
        }
        return ans[k-1];
    }
};

[20/07/23, 9:16:33 AM] Satvik Saini: int findKthPositive(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
        vector<int> ans;
        int prev = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<arr.size();i++){
            if(arr[i]-prev>1){
                while(arr[i]-prev!=1){
                    ans.push_back(prev+1);
                    if(ans.size()==k){
                        return ans[k-1];
                    }
                    prev++;
                }
            }
            prev = arr[i];
        }
        for(int i=arr[arr.size()-1]+1;i<=1000-arr.size();i++){
            ans.push_back(i);
            if(ans.size()==k){
                return ans[k-1];
            }
        }
        return ans[k-1];
    }
[20/07/23, 9:19:45 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    int findKthPositive(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
        int s =0,n = arr.size();
        // int e = arr.size()-1;
        int counter = 0;
        if(arr[0] != 1){
                counter = arr[0] -1;
            }
        if(n==1) return counter;
        while(s<n-1){
            if(arr[s] + 1 != arr[s+1]){
                counter += arr[s+1] - arr[s] -1 ;     
                if(counter >= k){
                     counter = counter - arr[s+1] - arr[s] -1;
                }
            } 
            s++;
        }
        std::cout<<"i am outside ";
        
        return arr[n-1] + k - counter;
        
    }
};

        for(int i=0;i<prices.size();i++){
            if(minsofar>prices[i]) minsofar = prices[i];
            max_profit = max(prices[i] - minsofar,max_profit);
        }
        return max_profit;
        
    }

[20/07/23, 6:02:28 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    void nextPermutation(vector<int>& arr) {
        int mini = INT_MAX,mini_idx = 0;
        for(int i=arr.size()-1 ; i>0 ; i--){
            if(arr[i]<arr[mini_idx]){
                mini_idx = i;
            }
        }
        int i = mini_idx + 1;
        int curr_grt = arr[i];
        int max_grt = INT_MIN;
        int just_grt_idx;
        while(i<arr.size()){
            if(arr[i] > arr[mini_idx]){
                curr_grt = arr[i];
                if(curr_grt < max_grt){
                    max_grt = curr_grt;
                    just_grt_idx = i;
                }

            }  
            i++;

        }
        swap(arr[mini_idx],arr[just_grt_idx]);
        sort(arr.begin() + mini_idx , arr.end());

       
        
    }
};

                    just_grt_idx = i;

[20/07/23, 6:19:50 PM] Satvik Saini: void nextPermutation(vector<int>& nums) {
        int c=0;
        int n =nums.size();
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            if(nums[i]<=nums[i-1]) c++;
        }
        if(c==n-1){
            sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
            return;
        }
        int swap_idx = 0;
        for(int i=n-1;i>0;i--){
            if(nums[i-1]<nums[i]){
                swap_idx = i-1;
                break;
            }
        }
        int just_greater=0,diff = INT_MAX;
        for(int i=swap_idx+1;i<n;i++){
            if(nums[i]>nums[swap_idx]){
               int temp = diff;
               diff = min(diff,nums[i] - nums[swap_idx]);
               if(temp!=diff) just_greater = i;
            }
        }
        swap(nums[just_greater],nums[swap_idx]);
        sort(nums.begin()+swap_idx+1,nums.end());
        return;
        
    }

                lsf = prices[i]; // update our least so far
            }
            pist = prices[i] - lsf; // calculating profit if sold today by, Buy - sell
            if(op < pist){ // if pist is more then our previous overall profit
                op = pist; // update overall profit
            }
        }
        return op; // return op

[21/07/23, 6:12:02 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: https://leetcode.com/problems/find-all-duplicates-in-an-array/description/
[21/07/23, 6:13:41 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:

    vector<int> findDuplicates(vector<int>& arr) {
        vector<int> ans;
        int i=0,n=arr.size();
        while(i<n){
            if(arr[i]!=i+1){
                swap(arr[i],arr[arr[i]-1]);
            }
            else{
                i++;
            }
        }
        for(int i=0 ; i<n-1 ; i++){
            if(arr[i] == arr[i+1]){
                ans.push_back(arr[i]);
            }
        }
        return ans;        
    }
};
[21/07/23, 6:29:39 PM] Satvik Saini: This C++ function, findDuplicates, takes a reference to a vector of integers called nums as input and returns another vector, ans, containing the duplicate elements that occur in the input vector nums. The function assumes that each element can occur at most twice in the input array, and the range of numbers in the array is between 1 and n, where n is the size of the input array.

Here's a step-by-step explanation of how the code works:

Check if the input vector nums is empty. If it is empty, the function immediately returns an empty vector since there are no elements to check for duplicates.

Initialize an empty vector of integers called ans, which will be used to store the duplicate elements found in the nums array.

Loop through each element in the nums array using a for loop with the index i.

Inside the loop, there is a conditional check to determine if the current element has already been encountered before. This is done using the value of the element itself. Let's break down the key part of this check:

cpp
Copy code
if (nums[abs(nums[i]) - 1] < 0)
abs(nums[i]) gets the absolute value of the current element at index i. This is done to handle both positive and negative values since the duplicates might be present in both directions.

nums[abs(nums[i]) - 1] accesses the element at the corresponding index (minus one to account for zero-based indexing) in the nums array.

The condition nums[abs(nums[i]) - 1] < 0 checks if the value at the corresponding index is negative. If it is, it means the current element has already been encountered before.

If the current element has been encountered before (i.e., it has a negative value at the corresponding index), we consider it as a duplicate, and we add its absolute value to the ans vector.

After handling the duplicate check, we modify the array nums to mark the current element as seen. We do this by making the value at the corresponding index (minus one) negative.

cpp
Copy code
nums[abs(nums[i]) - 1] = -nums[abs(nums[i]) - 1];
This step ensures that when we encounter the same element again in the future, the check in step 4 will correctly identify it as a duplicate.

Repeat steps 4 to 6 for all elements in the nums array.

Once the loop is complete, the ans vector will contain all the duplicate elements found in the nums array. Return this ans vector as the final result.

To summarize, the code leverages the fact that each element in the array is in the range [1, n], where n is the size of the array. By using negative values as markers, it efficiently identifies and collects duplicate elements in the ans vector while modifying the nums array in place. The time complexity of this function is O(n), where n is the size of the input vector.
[21/07/23, 6:30:44 PM] Satvik Saini: Here's a step-by-step explanation of the code:

vector<int> findDuplicates(vector<int>& nums) {

This line defines a function called findDuplicates that takes a reference to a vector of integers (nums) as input and returns a vector of integers as output.
if (nums.empty()) return {};

This line checks if the input vector nums is empty. If it is empty, the function immediately returns an empty vector {} as there are no elements to process.
vector<int> ans;

This line declares an empty vector ans to store the duplicate elements found in the input array.
for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {

This is a loop that iterates through each element of the nums vector. The loop variable i represents the index of the current element being processed.
if (nums[abs(nums[i]) - 1] < 0)

This line checks if the element at index abs(nums[i]) - 1 (considering 0-based indexing) of the nums vector is already negative. If it is negative, it means that the current element has been encountered before (as it appeared twice), making it a duplicate.
ans.push_back(abs(nums[i]));

If the current element is a duplicate, its absolute value (to handle negative numbers) is pushed into the ans vector, as it is one of the duplicate elements.
nums[abs(nums[i]) - 1] = -nums[abs(nums[i]) - 1];

Regardless of whether the current element is a duplicate or not, this line negates the value of the element at index abs(nums[i]) - 1 to mark its occurrence. This step ensures that when the same element is encountered again, the condition in step 5 will be true, identifying it as a duplicate.
return ans;

Finally, the function returns the ans vector containing all the duplicate elements found during the iteration.
In summary, the code efficiently finds duplicate elements in the given array and stores them in a new vector. The algorithm takes advantage of the range of numbers in the array being between 1 and n and utilizes negative values to keep track of duplicate occurrences while preserving the original data.
[21/07/23, 6:32:31 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: The given code is a C++ solution to find duplicates in an array of integers, represented by the vector `nums`. The goal is to return a vector containing all the elements that appear more than once in the input array.

Let's break down the logic behind the code step by step:

1. Check if the input vector `nums` is empty. If it is, return an empty vector `ans` immediately since there are no elements to find duplicates for.

2. Initialize an empty vector `ans` to store the duplicates found in the `nums` array.

3. Loop through each element in the `nums` array using a `for` loop with the index `i` ranging from 0 to the size of the array `nums`.

4. Within the loop, we use a technique based on the array indices to keep track of whether an element has been encountered before or not.

5. For each element `nums[i]`, we check if the value at the index corresponding to the absolute value of `nums[i]` minus 1 (i.e., `abs(nums[i])-1`) is negative or not.

    a. If it is negative, it means we have encountered this element before, and it is a duplicate. So, we add the absolute value of `nums[i]` to the `ans` vector.

    b. If it is not negative, it means we have not encountered this element before, and it is the first occurrence. In this case, we update the value at the index corresponding to the absolute value of `nums[i]` minus 1 to its negative value. This marks the element as encountered.

6. By the end of the loop, we would have identified all the duplicate elements and added them to the `ans` vector. The duplicates are added in the order they appear in the input array.

7. Finally, we return the `ans` vector containing all the duplicates found in the `nums` array.

The clever part of this solution is that it utilizes the input array itself as a data structure to keep track of whether an element has been encountered before. By using the element values as indices and changing the sign of the value at that index, the algorithm can mark elements as seen without using any extra memory for a hash table or set. This approach reduces the space complexity to O(1) since the additional memory used for storing the duplicates is the output vector `ans`, and the space for the input vector `nums` is not counted. The time complexity of this solution is O(n), where n is the number of elements in the input vector `nums`.
[21/07/23, 6:49:59 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: Approach
The provided solution uses the Negation Technique to find duplicates in an array. Here's a breakdown of the solution:

Create an empty result list to store the duplicate elements.

Iterate through the array nums using a for loop, starting from index 0 and going up to the last index (nums.length - 1).

For each element at index i, calculate its absolute value by using Math.abs(nums[i]). This step is performed to handle negative numbers since we will be using the array elements themselves as indicators.

Subtract 1 from the absolute value obtained in the previous step and store it in the index variable. This is done because array indices are 0-based, while the elements in the array start from 1.

Check the value at the index index in the nums array. If it is negative, it means that we have already encountered the number before (since we have negated it during the iteration). In this case, add index + 1 to the result list, indicating that index + 1 is a duplicate number.

Negate the value at the index in the nums array by multiplying it by -1. This step marks the number as seen by making it negative.

After iterating through the entire array, the result list will contain all the duplicate elements.

Finally, return the result list containing the duplicate numbers.

This solution achieves a time complexity of O(n) since it iterates through the array once. It also uses constant space, as it does not require any additional data structures apart from the input array and the result list.

Important ------>>>>>> this negation approach only works if maximum value in array is either less then length of an array or equal to an array's length
[22/07/23, 9:51:16 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: https://leetcode.com/problems/set-matrix-zeroes/
[22/07/23, 5:50:23 PM] Satvik Saini: vector<int> findDuplicates(vector<int>& nums) {
       // if(nums.size() == 0) return {};
        vector<int> ans;
        int n = nums.size();

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            nums[(nums[i]%n)-1]+=n+1;
        }

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(nums[i]/n>=2){
                ans.push_back(i+1);
            }
        }

        return ans;

[24/07/23, 5:56:10 PM] Satvik Saini: int partitionDisjoint(vector<int>& nums) {
        if(nums.size()==2 && nums[0]==nums[1]) return 1;
        int prev_p=-1;
        int ele = nums[0];

        for(int i=nums.size()-1;i>=0;i--){
            if(nums[i]<ele){
                prev_p = i+1;
                break;
            }
        }
        if(prev_p==-1) return 1;
        int curr_p;

        for(int i=1;i<prev_p;i++){
            ele = nums[i];
            for(int j=nums.size()-1;j>=0;j--){
                if(nums[j]<ele){
                    curr_p = j+1;
                    if(curr_p>prev_p){
                        prev_p = curr_p;
                    }
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        return prev_p;
        
    }

using namespace std;
void makeallbinary(string& inp){

	cout<<"infunction";
	//base case
	if(inp.empty()){
		cout<<inp<<" ";
		return;
	}

	//recursive case

	if(inp[0] == '?'){
		inp[0] = '0';
		makeallbinary(inp.substr(1));

		inp[0] = '1';
		makeallbinary(inp.substr(1));
	}
	else{
		makeallbinary(inp.substr(1));
	}

}

	}

	return 0;
}

[25/07/23, 8:54:56 PM] Satvik Saini: #include<iostream>
#include<vector>
using namespace std;

void subset(int arr[],int n, int target, int j, int &cnt, vector<int> v){
	//base case
	if(target<0 || j==n){
		return;
	}
	if(target==0){
		for(int i=0;i<v.size();i++){
			cout<<v[i]<<" ";
		}
		cout<<" ";
		cnt++;
		return;
	}

	//recursive case
	for(int i=j;i<n;i++){
		if(arr[i]<=target){
			v.push_back(arr[i]);
			subset(arr,n,target-arr[i],j+1,cnt,v);
			v.pop_back();
		}
	}
}

int main() {
	int n;
	cin>>n;
	int arr[n];
	for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
		cin>>arr[i];
	}
	int target;
	cin>>target;
	int cnt = 0;
	vector<int> v;
	subset(arr,n,target,0,cnt,v);
	cout<<endl;
	cout<<cnt<<endl;
	return 0;
}

using namespace std;
void makeallbinary(string inp,string out){

	//base case
	if(inp.empty()){
	// cout<<"infunction";
		cout<<out<<" ";
		return;
	}

	//recursive case

	if(inp[0] == '?'){
		out += '0';
		makeallbinary(inp.substr(1),out);
		out.pop_back();

		out += '1';
		makeallbinary(inp.substr(1),out);
		out.pop_back();

	}
	else{
		out+=inp[0];
		makeallbinary(inp.substr(1),out);
		out.pop_back();
	}

}

using namespace std;

void bin_str(string inp, string out){

	//base case
	if(inp.empty()){
		for(int i=0;i<out.size();i++){
			cout<<out[i];
		}
		cout<<" ";
		return;
	}

	//recursive case

	if(inp[0] == '?'){
		out+='0';
		bin_str(inp.substr(1),out);
		out.pop_back();

		out+='1';
		bin_str(inp.substr(1),out);

		out.pop_back();
	}
	else{
		out+=inp[0];
		bin_str(inp.substr(1),out);
		out.pop_back();
	}

}

[27/07/23, 11:14:26 AM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/string-to-integer-atoi/
[27/07/23, 11:14:43 AM] Satvik Saini: "words and 987"
[27/07/23, 11:28:06 AM] Satvik Saini: void str_to_i(string s, int i, int &out,bool &flag){
        cout<<out<<" ";
        //base case
        if(s[i] == '\0'){
            return;
        }

        //recursive case
        if(s[i]==' '){
            str_to_i(s,i+1,out,flag);
        }
        else if (s[i]=='-'){
           flag = true;
           str_to_i(s,i+1,out,flag);
        }
        else if(s[i]-'0'>=0 && s[i]-'0'<=9){
            string str = out+'0';
            str+=s[i];
            out = str - '0';
            str_to_i(s,i+1,out,flag);
        }
        else{
            return;
        }
    }

    int myAtoi(string s) {
        int ans = 0;
        bool flag = false;
        str_to_i(s,0,ans,flag);
        if(flag) return -ans;
        return ans;
    }

public:
    void givenumtillnow(string s , int& ans, bool& flag){
        //base casee
        if(s.empty()){
            return;
        }
        if(s[0] != ' ' and s[0] != '-' and s[0]!= '+' and (s[0]-'0' < 0 || s[0]-'0' > 9)){
            return;
        }
        
        //recursive case
        

        if(s[0] == ' '){
            givenumtillnow(s.substr(1),ans,flag);
        }
        else if(s[0] == '-'){
            flag = false;
            givenumtillnow(s.substr(1),ans,flag);

        }
        else if(s[0]-'0'>=0 && s[0] - '0'<= 9){
            int tempnum = s[0]-'0';
            ans = 10*ans + tempnum;
            givenumtillnow(s.substr(1),ans,flag);
        }
        else{
            return;
        }
    }
    int myAtoi(string s) {
        int ans =0;
        bool flag = true;
        givenumtillnow(s,ans,flag);
        if(flag) return ans;
        else{
            return -ans;
        }
        


        
    }

        //base casee

        //recursive case

            flag = false;

public:
    void givenumtillnow(string s ,long long int& ans, bool& flag){
        //base casee
        std::cout<<"inside function"<<ans;

        if(s.empty()){
            return;
        }
        if(s[0]=='+' and (s[1]-'0' < 0 || s[1]-'0' > 9)){
            ans = 0;
            return;
        }if(s[0]=='-' and (s[1]-'0' < 0 || s[1]-'0' > 9)){
            ans = 0;
            return;
        }
        if(s[0] != ' ' and s[0] != '-' and s[0]!= '+' and (s[0]-'0' < 0 || s[0]-'0' > 9)){
            return;
        }
        //recursive case
        if(s[0] == ' '){
            givenumtillnow(s.substr(1),ans,flag);
        }
        else if(s[0] == '-'){
            flag = false;
            givenumtillnow(s.substr(1),ans,flag);
        }else if(s[0] == '+'){
            flag = true;
            givenumtillnow(s.substr(1),ans,flag);
        }
        else if(s[0]-'0'>=0 && s[0] - '0'<= 9){
            int tempnum = s[0]-'0';
            ans = 10*ans + tempnum;
            if(ans > INT_MAX and flag){
                ans = INT_MAX;
                return;
            }
            else if(ans > INT_MAX and !flag){
                ans = INT_MIN;
                return;
            }
            else{
              givenumtillnow(s.substr(1),ans,flag);
            }
        }else{
            return;        
        }
    }
    int myAtoi(string s) {
        long long int ans =0;
        bool flag = true;
        givenumtillnow(s,ans,flag);
        if(!flag and ans == INT_MIN){
            return INT_MIN;
        }
        if(flag) return (int)ans;
        else{
            return -(int)ans;
        }       
    }

void multiply(string s1, char a,int &num,int & carry){

	//base case
	if(s1.empty()){
		cout<<num<<endl;
		return;
	}
	//recursive case
	int temp2 = a-'0';
	int temp = s1[0] - '0';
	int product = temp*temp2;
	num = num*10 + product%10 + carry;
	product/=10;
	carry = product;
	multiply( s1, a,num,carry);
}

[29/07/23, 11:12:33 AM] Satvik Saini: istNode* reverseBetween(ListNode* head, int left, int right) {
        if(!head || !head->next || left == right) return head;

        ListNode* left_node = getnode(left,head);
        ListNode* right_node = getnode(right,head);
        ListNode* prev = NULL;
        ListNode* after_right = getnode(right+1,head);

        if(left>1){
            prev = getnode(left-1,head);
        }
        if(prev!=NULL) prev->next = right_node;
        else head = right_node;

        ListNode* prev1 = left_node;
        ListNode* curr = left_node->next;
        ListNode* forward = curr->next;
        while(curr != after_right){
            forward = curr->next;
            curr->next = prev1;
            prev1 = curr;
            curr = forward;
        }
        left_node->next = after_right;

        return head;
    }

[30/07/23, 8:00:44 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* swap(ListNode* head){
        //base case
        if(!head){
            return NULL;
        }

        //recursive case
        int i=0;
        ListNode* curr = head->next;
        ListNode* prev = head;
        ListNode* forward = head;

        while(i<1 && curr!=NULL){
            forward = curr->next;
            curr->next = prev;
            prev = curr;
            curr = forward;
            i++;
        }
        ListNode* headfromfriend = swap(curr);
        head->next = headfromfriend;

        return prev;
    }

    void swap_pair(ListNode* &head){
        if(!head || !head->next) return;
        
        head = swap(head);
        return;
    }
};

[01/08/23, 7:24:05 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    int generateprime(int i){
        int arr[4] = {2,3,5,7};
        return arr[i-1];
    }
    void countgoodstring(string out,long long n,int i,int& count){

        //base case
        if(i == n ){
            count++;
            return;
        }
        //recursive case
        if(i%2 == 0){
            for(int k=0 ; k<10 ; k = k+2){
                out.push_back(k+'0');
                countgoodstring(out,n,i+1,count);
                out.pop_back();
            } 
        }
        else{
            for(int k=1 ; k<=4 ; k++){
                char str = generateprime(k) + '0';
                out.push_back(str);
                countgoodstring(out,n,i+1,count);
                out.pop_back();
            }
        }
    }
    int countGoodNumbers(long long n) {
        int count =0;
        string output;

        countgoodstring(output,long long n,0,count);
        return count;

        
    }
};
[02/08/23, 10:08:27 AM] Satvik Saini: void permute(string s, vector<string> &ans, int i){
        //base case
        if(i == s.length()){
            ans.push_back(s);
            return;
        }

        //recursive case
        for(int j=i;j<s.length();j++){
            swap(s[i],s[j]);
            permute(s,ans,i+1);
            swap(s[i],s[j]);
        }
    }

    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
        string s;
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            s.push_back(i+'0');
        }
        vector<string> ans;
        permute(s,ans,0);

        sort(ans.begin(),ans.end());
        for(int i=0;i<ans.size();i++){
           cout<<ans[i]<<" ";
        }
        return ans[k-1];
    }

[02/08/23, 12:39:47 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    void permute(string s, string& ans, int i, int k, int &cnt){
        //base case
        if(i == s.length()){
            cnt++;
            if(cnt == k) {
                ans = s;
            }
            return;
        }

        // if(cnt == k) {
        //     ans.push_back(s);
        //     return;
        // }

        //recursive case
        for(int j=i;j<s.length();j++){
            swap(s[i],s[j]);
            permute(s,ans,i+1,k,cnt);
            swap(s[i],s[j]);
        }
    }

    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
        string s;
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            s.push_back(i+'0');
        }
        string ans;
        int counter=0;
        permute(s,ans,0,k,counter);

        // sort(ans.begin(),ans.end());
        // for(int i=0;i<ans.size();i++){
        //    cout<<ans[i]<<" ";
        // }
        return ans;
    }
};

[02/08/23, 12:53:54 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
        int fact=1;
        vector<int>numbers;
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++)
        {
            fact=fact*i;
            numbers.push_back(i);
        }
        numbers.push_back(n);
        string ans ="";
        k=k-1;
        while(true)
        {
            ans=ans+to_string(numbers[k/fact]);
            numbers.erase(numbers.begin()+k/fact);
            if(numbers.size()==0) break;
            k=k%fact;
            fact=fact/numbers.size();
        }
        return ans;
        
        
    }
};

//First find (n-1)!
//ex:
//1 2 3 4
// push all numbers in a vector in sorted order
// as total number of permutation formed is 4! , it is divided equally ,like first (n-1)! numbers starts with 1 , next (n-1)! starts with 2...and so on.
// now find the first number.
//     To find the first number , we divide k/fact it will give the index of the first number in the vector in which number is stored...add that number in the string and remove that number from the vector...now rest operation will take place on numbers left.
// update k to k % fact
// and fact to fact / size of vector , 
// now again loop will run and find the position of 2nd number in the vector add it to the string and again do the same opeartion

[02/08/23, 1:14:17 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    void f(vector<int>& nums,int i,set< vector<int> >& ans_set,vector<int>& ans){


        //base case
        if(i == nums.size()){
            ans_set.insert(ans);
            return;
        }


        //recursive case
        //you have not included arr[i]in the ans vector 
        f(nums,i+1,ans_set,ans);//ask friend to do for rest
        //you have included arr[i] in the ans vector 
        ans.push_back(nums[i]);
        f(nums,i+1,ans_set,ans);//ask friend to do for rest
        ans.pop_back();//backtrack kardo 



    }
    vector<vector<int>> subsetsWithDup(vector<int>& nums) {
        set< vector<int> > ans_set;
        vector<int> ans;
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        f(nums,0,ans_set,ans);
        vector<vector<int>> fin_ans;
        for(auto x:ans_set){
            fin_ans.push_back(x);
        }
        return fin_ans;

        

    }
};
[02/08/23, 1:18:13 PM] Satvik Saini: void subset_2(vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& out,vector<vector<int>>& ans, int i){
        //base case
        // if(i == nums.size()){
            ans.push_back(out);
            // return;
        // }

        //recursive case
        for(int j=i;j<nums.size();j++){
            if(j>i && nums[j] == nums[j-1]) continue;
            out.push_back(nums[j]);
            subset_2(nums,out,ans,j+1);
            out.pop_back();
        }
    }

    vector<vector<int>> subsetsWithDup(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        vector<int> out;
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        subset_2(nums,out,ans,0);
        return ans;
    }

        //base case

        ans.push_back(out);

        //recursive case
        
        for(int j=i;j<nums.size();j++){
            if(j>i && nums[j] == nums[j-1]) continue;
            out.push_back(nums[j]);
            subset_2(nums,out,ans,j+1);
            out.pop_back();
        }
    }

    vector<vector<int>> subsetsWithDup(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        vector<int> out;
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        subset_2(nums,out,ans,0);
        return ans;
    }

[03/08/23, 12:23:24 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: int checknei(vector<vector<int>> board,int i,int j,int m,int n){
        int dx[8] = {-1,-1,-1,0,1,1,-1};
        int dy[8] = {-1,0,1,1,1,0,-1,-1};

        int count = 0;

        for(int k=0 ; k<8 ; k++){
            if((i+dx[k] >= 0 or i+dx[k]<=m-1) and (j+dy[k]>=0 or j+dy[k]<=n-1)){
                if(board[i+dx[k]][j+dy[k]] == 1) count ++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
