[11/10/23, 7:25:19 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: /*

Given an directed graph, check if there exists a back-edge or not.

*/

#include<iostream>
#include<unordered_map>
#include<unordered_set>
#include<list>
#include<queue>

using namespace std;

template <typename T>
class graph {

	unordered_map<T, list<T>> neighbourMap; // to store the graph representation

public :

	void addEdge(T u, T v) {
		// add a directed edge between vertex 'u' and 'v'
		neighbourMap[u].push_back(v);
	}

	void topologicalSort() {

		queue<T> q; // to keep track of vertices w/o any dependencies
		unordered_map<T, int> inDegMap; // to store the mapping b/w the
		// vertices and their in-degrees

		// populate the inDegMap

		for (pair<T, list<T>> vertex : neighbourMap) {
			list<T> neighbourList = vertex.second;
			for (T neighbour : neighbourList) {
				// account for directed edge from 'vertex' to 'neighbour'
				inDegMap[neighbour]++;
			}
		}

		// initialise queue with vertices w/o
		// any dependency i.e. zero in-degree

		for (pair<T, list<T>> vertex : neighbourMap) {
			T vertexLabel = vertex.first;
			if (inDegMap.find(vertexLabel) == inDegMap.end()) {
				// vertex with 'vertexLabel' has no dependency
				q.push(vertexLabel);
			}
		}

		while (!q.empty()) {
			T front = q.front();
			q.pop();

			// explore 'front'

			cout << front << " ";

			list<T> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
			for (T neighbour : neighbourList) {
				inDegMap[neighbour]--;
				if (inDegMap[neighbour] == 0) {
					// depencies of 'neighbour' have been resolved
					q.push(neighbour);
				}
			}

		}

		cout << endl;

	}

};


int main() {

	graph<char> g;

	g.addEdge('A', 'B');
	g.addEdge('A', 'C');
	g.addEdge('A', 'D');
	g.addEdge('B', 'D');
	g.addEdge('B', 'E');
	g.addEdge('D', 'C');
	g.addEdge('D', 'E');
	g.addEdge('D', 'F');
	g.addEdge('D', 'G');
	g.addEdge('D', 'H');
	g.addEdge('E', 'G');
	g.addEdge('F', 'C');
	g.addEdge('G', 'H');
	g.addEdge('H', 'F');

	g.topologicalSort();

	return 0;
}
[11/10/23, 7:25:52 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include<iostream>
#include<list>
#include<unordered_map>
#include<unordered_set>
#include<queue>

using namespace std;


template <typename T>
class graph{
    bool isdirected;
    unordered_map<T , list<T> > neighbourMap;
    
    public:

    graph(bool flag = false){
        this->isdirected = flag;   
    }

    void addedge(T a , T b){
        // add an edge between a and b 
        // this means a become neighbour of b and b becomes neighbour of a 
        neighbourMap[a].push_back(b);
        if(!isdirected){
            neighbourMap[b].push_back(a);
        }
    }

    void print(){
        // iterate in te neighbour map 
        for(pair<T , list<T> >  P : neighbourMap){
            T vertex = P.first;
            list<T> neighbours = P.second;
            cout<<vertex<<" : ";
            for(T x : neighbours){
                cout<<x<<" ";
            }  
            cout<<endl;
        }
    }

    void dfs_helper(unordered_set<T>&  visited , T src){

        // surce ko visit karlo 
        visited.insert(src);
        cout<<src<<" ";


        // source ke unvisited bacho ke lie dfs call krdo

        for( T neighbour : neighbourMap[src]){
            if(visited.find(neighbour) == visited.end()){
                // unvisted neighbour ke lie dfs call krdoo 
                dfs_helper(visited , neighbour);
            }
        }
    }

    void dfs(T src){// you will be given a source node , and you have to traverse it using dfs

    unordered_set<T>  visited;
    cout<<"dfs("<<src<<") : ";
    dfs_helper(visited , src);
    cout<<endl;
    }


    void bfs(T src){

        queue<T> q;
        q.push(src);
        unordered_set<T> visited;
        visited.insert(src);
        vector<T> bfs;
        // queue will store all the visited and unexplored elements 
        // JO BHI ELEMENT Q se remove hoga voh bfs me add hoga and jo bhi element q me currently hoga voh hamesha visited hoga , jo bhi pop hoga uske voh bachhe jo visited nhi h unko q me add krdenge and then yeh kaam repeat higa , q ke front ko process karenge , uske bachoo ko handle karenge 
        
        while (!q.empty()){
            
            // remove the front element 
            // process the front element :- remove it from queue and add it in the bfs vector 
            T front = q.front;
            q.pop();
            bfs.push_back(front);
            list<T> Neighbours = neighbourMap[front];

            for(T neighbour : Neighbours){
                if(visited.find(front) == visited.end()){
                    // not visited 
                    visited.insert(neighbour);
                    q.push(neighbour);
                }
            }
            // put all the neighbour of front in the queue and mark them visited 
        }
    }
    void traversal(){ 
        // this is mainly done to tackle disconnected grapsh as well 
        unordered_set<T> visited;
        for( pair<T , list<T> > k : neighbourMap){
            T vertex = k.first;
            if(visited.find(vertex) == visited.end()){
                // not visited the call either bfs or dfs on this as it will act as a source node and all the nodes connected to it will be traversed 
                dfs_helper(visited , vertex); 
            }
        }
    }
    bool dfs_helper(T source , T parent ,unordered_set<T>& visited ){
        // we will assume parent of source is source initailly 
        // apply normal dfs 
        // basic idea is if we find a nieghbour which has been visited and also is not the parent then we return ture or we continue our search in the graph and if not cycle is found we return false;
        // in order to accomplish this , we need to pass the parent of each source vertex as well so that whenever we get a vertex which has been visited , we can chech if it is a parent or not 

        // source ko insert krdo visited me 
        visited.insert(source);

        list<T> neighbours = neighbourMap[source];

        for( T neighbour : neighbours){
            if(visited.find(neighbour) == visited.end()){
                // the current neighbour has not been visited before so now you explore all possibilities from the neighbour vertex
               if( dfs_helper(neighbour , source , visited )){
                return true;
               }
            }
            else{
                // you have a neighbour which has been visited 
                if(neighbour != parent){
                    return true;
                }

            }
        }
        return false;

    }
    
    bool iscyclepresent (){
        // iterate on all components and check for a cycle
        unordered_set<T> visited;
        for(pair<T , list<T> > v : neighbourMap){
            T vertex = v.first;
            if(visited.find(vertex) == visited.end()){
                // not visited :: new component 
                if(dfs_helper(vertex , vertex , visited)){  // will return bool is called on each component basically 
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
    bool bfs_helper(unordered_map<T , int >& colormap , T source ){
        // our main idea is to find a neighbour which is colored and has the color same as the color of the source block 
        // initialise the queue
        queue<T> q;
        q.push(source);
        colormap[source] = 0;

        // iterate and explore the elements of the queue
        while(!q.empty()){
            // bfs means pop and explore the list 
            T front = q.front();
            q.pop();
            int front_color = colormap[front];

            list<T> neighbours = neighbourMap[front];
            for( T neighbour : neighbours){
                if(colormap.find(neighbour) == colormap.end()){
                    // not there in the color map 
                    // put in there with oppsite colour of front
                    colormap[neighbour] = front_color ? 0 : 1;
                    q.push(neighbour);
                }else{
                    // this neighbour is in the colormap
                    if(colormap[neighbour] == front_color){
                        return false;
                       // we have found a neighbour which has same color as the source 
                    }

                }
            }
            return true;
        }

    }
    bool isbipartite(){
        bool flag = true;
        unordered_map<T , int > colorMap;
        for( pair<T , list<T> > P : neighbourMap){
            T vertex = P.first;
            // agar koi component colrmap me nhi hai that means ke humne us component pr bfs call nhi ia hai , kyuke bfs call on a connected component will cover al the vetrices 

            if(colorMap.find(vertex) == colorMap.end()){
                // new component 
                if(bfs_helper(colorMap , vertex) == false){
                    // you have a component which is not bipartite 
                    flag = false;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        return flag;
    }
    bool dfs_helper2(unordered_set<T>& visited , T source , unordered_set<T>& function_stk){

        visited.insert(source);
        function_stk.push(source);
         // now check if the nieghbour is visited or not 
        list<T> neighbourList = neighbourMap[source];
        for(T neighbour : neighbourList){
            if(visited.find(neighbour) == visited.end()){
                return dfs_helper2(visited , neighbour , function_stk);
            }else{
                //agar meri neighbour list me already koi visited h then there should be a path from the neighbour to the source node means ke 
                if(function_stk.find(neighbour) != function_stk.end()){
                    //neighbour is present on the function call stack
					// there exists a directed path from neighbour to source
					// i.e
					// source -> neighbour is a backedge
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }
        function_stk.erase(source);
        return false;  
    }

    bool directed_backedge(){
        unordered_set<T> visited;
        for(pair<T,list<T> > p : neighbourMap){
            T vertexLabel = p.first;
            if(visited.find(vertexLabel) == visited.end()){
                // a new component is encountered
                unordered_set<T> function_stk;
                if(dfs_helper2(visited , vertexLabel , function_stk)){
                    return true;
                }
            }

        }
        return false;
    }
    void topologicalsort(){
        queue<T> q;
        unordered_map<T,int> indegreeMap;

        // populate the in degree map 
        // iterate in the neighbour map
        // populating the elements in the indegree map  
        for( pair<T , list<T> > p : neighbourMap){
            list<T> neighbourlist = p.second;
            for(T neighbour : neighbourlist ){
                indegreeMap[neighbour]++;
            }
        }
        
        for(pair<T , int > p : indegreeMap){
            T vertex_label = p.first;
            // if the dependency of tis neighbour becomes 
            cout<<vertex_label<<" ";
        }
        cout<<endl;
        
        // placing 0 indegree ones in queue 
        for(pair<T , list<T> > p : neighbourMap){
            T vertex_label = p.first;
            // if the dependency of tis neighbour becomes 
            if(indegreeMap.find(vertex_label) == indegreeMap.end()){
                q.push(vertex_label);
            }
        }
        // iterate on queue an pop and process the elements 
        while(!q.empty()){

            T front = q.front();
            q.pop();
            cout<<front<<" ";

            // process the 0 indegree element
            // reduce the indegree of all the neighbours of the front element 
            list<T> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
            for(T neighbour : neighbourList){
                indegreeMap[neighbour]--;
                if(indegreeMap[neighbour] == 0){
                    q.push(neighbour);
                }
            }
        }
}
    

};

[11/10/23, 7:28:13 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include<iostream>
#include<list>
#include<unordered_map>
#include<unordered_set>
#include<queue>

using namespace std;


template <typename T>
class graph{
    bool isdirected;
    unordered_map<T , list<T> > neighbourMap;
    
    public:

    graph(bool flag = false){
        this->isdirected = flag;   
    }

    void addedge(T a , T b){
        // add an edge between a and b 
        // this means a become neighbour of b and b becomes neighbour of a 
        neighbourMap[a].push_back(b);
        if(!isdirected){
            neighbourMap[b].push_back(a);
        }
    }

    void topologicalsort(){
        queue<T> q;
        unordered_map<T,int> indegreeMap;

        // populate the in degree map 
        // iterate in the neighbour map
        // populating the elements in the indegree map  
        for( pair<T , list<T> > p : neighbourMap){
            list<T> neighbourlist = p.second;
            for(T neighbour : neighbourlist ){
                indegreeMap[neighbour]++;
            }
        }
        
        for(pair<T , int > p : indegreeMap){
            T vertex_label = p.first;
            // if the dependency of this neighbour becomes 
            cout<<vertex_label<<" ";
        }
        cout<<endl;
        
        // placing 0 indegree ones in queue 
        for(pair<T , list<T> > p : neighbourMap){
            T vertex_label = p.first;
            // if the dependency of tis neighbour becomes 
            if(indegreeMap.find(vertex_label) == indegreeMap.end()){
                q.push(vertex_label);
            }
        }
        // iterate on queue an pop and process the elements 
        while(!q.empty()){

            T front = q.front();
            q.pop();
            cout<<front<<" ";

            // process the 0 indegree element
            // reduce the indegree of all the neighbours of the front element 
            list<T> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
            for(T neighbour : neighbourList){
                indegreeMap[neighbour]--;
                if(indegreeMap[neighbour] == 0){
                    q.push(neighbour);
                }
            }
        }
}
    

};

[13/10/23, 10:53:13 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int orangesRotting(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {

        int m = grid.size();
        int n = grid[0].size();

        vector<vector<int>> dist(m,vector<int>(n,INT_MIN));

        queue<pair<int,int>> q;

        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                if(grid[i][j] == 2){
                    q.push({i,j});
                    dist[i][j] = 0;
                }
            }
        }

        vector<int> dx = {0,0,1,-1};
        vector<int> dy = {1,-1,0,0};

        while(!q.empty()){
            pair<int,int> front = q.front();
            q.pop();
            int i = front.first;
            int j = front.second;

            for(int k=0;k<4;k++){
                int ii = i + dx[k];
                int jj = j + dy[k];

                if(ii >= 0 && ii < m && j >= 0 && j < n && grid[ii][jj] == 1){
                    grid[ii][jj] = 2;
                    dist[ii][jj] = dist[i][j] + 1;
                    q.push({ii,jj});
                }
            }
        }

        int ans = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                if(grid[i][j] == 1){
                    return -1;
                }
                ans = max(ans,dist[i][j]);
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

[17/10/23, 9:29:28 PM] Satvik Saini: nt LadderTimeOptimised(int n, int k){
    vector<int> dp(n + 1);

    dp[0] = 1;
    dp[1] = dp[0];

    for (int i = 2; i <= k; i++){
        dp[i] = 2 * dp[i - 1];
    }

    for (int i = k + 1; i <= n; i++){
        dp[i] = 2 * dp[i - 1] - dp[i - k - 1]
    }
    return dp[n];
}

[21/10/23, 1:04:58 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: int bottomUphelper(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int n, int m){

        vector<vector<int>> dp(n+1 , vector<int>(m+1));
        for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
            dp[i][m] = INT_MAX;
        }for(int j=0 ; j<m ; j++){
            dp[n][j] = INT_MAX;
        }
        dp[n-1][m-1] = grid[n-1][m-1];
        for( int i=n ; i>=0 ; i--){
            for( int j=m ; j>=0 ; j--){
                dp[i][j] = grid[i][j] + min(dp[i+1][j] , dp[i][j+1]);
            }
        }

        return dp[0][0];

    }
‎[21/10/23, 1:14:12 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: ‎image omitted
[21/10/23, 1:15:40 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: int bottomUphelper(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int n, int m){

        vector<vector<int>> dp(n+1 , vector<int>(m+1));
        for(int i=0 ; i<=n ; i++){
            dp[i][m] = INT_MAX;
        }for(int j=0 ; j<=m ; j++){
            dp[n][j] = INT_MAX;
        }
        dp[n-1][m-1] = grid[n-1][m-1];
        for( int i=n-1 ; i>=0 ; i--){
            for( int j=m-1 ; j>=0 ; j--){
                if(i == n-1 && j == m-1) continue;

                dp[i][j] = grid[i][j] + min(dp[i+1][j] , dp[i][j+1]);
            }
        }

        return dp[0][0];

    }

[24/10/23, 10:17:37 AM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-number-of-steps-to-make-two-strings-anagram-ii/
[24/10/23, 10:17:43 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int minSteps(string s, string t) {
        unordered_map<char,int> mp1;
        unordered_map<char,int> mp2;
        
        for(int i=0;i<s.length();i++){
            mp1[s[i]]++;
        }
        for(int i=0;i<t.length();i++){
            mp2[t[i]]++;
        }
        
        int ans = 0;
        
        for(int i=0;i<s.length();i++){
            ans += abs(mp1[s[i]] - mp2[s[i]]);
            mp1[s[i]] = mp2[s[i]] = 0;
        }
        
        for(int i=0;i<t.length();i++){
            ans += abs(mp1[t[i]] - mp2[t[i]]);
        }
        
        return ans;
    }
};

[27/10/23, 7:40:28 AM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/apply-operations-to-make-two-strings-equal/
[27/10/23, 7:40:50 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int cost(string s1, string s2, int i, int j, int x){
        //base case
        if(i == s1.length()){
            return INT_MAX-x; // doubt
        }

        //recursive case
        if(s1[i] == s2[j]){
            return cost(s1, s2, i+1, j+1, x);
        }
        int ans = INT_MAX;
        if(i+1<s1.length() && s1[i+1] == s2[j]){
            swap(s1[i], s1[i+1]);
            ans = 1 + cost(s1, s2, i+1, j+1, x);
        }
        
        for(int k=i+2;k<s1.length();k++){
            if(s1[k] == s2[j]){
                swap(s1[i], s2[k]);
                ans = min(ans,x + cost(s1, s2, i+1, j+1, x));
            }
        }
        return ans == INT_MAX ? -1 : ans;
    }
    
    
    int minOperations(string s1, string s2, int x) {
        return cost(s1, s2, 0, 0, x);
    }
};
[27/10/23, 7:50:20 AM] Satvik Saini: "10110"
"00011"

[27/10/23, 7:56:33 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    int cost(string s1, string s2, int i, int j, int x){
        //base case
        if(i == s1.length()){
            cout<<s1<<" ";
            return INT_MAX-x; // doubt
        }

        //recursive case
        if(s1[i] == s2[j]){
            return cost(s1, s2, i+1, j+1, x);
        }
        int ans = INT_MAX;
        if(i+1<s1.length() && s1[i+1] == s2[j]){
            swap(s1[i], s1[i+1]);
            ans = 1 + cost(s1, s2, i+1, j+1, x);
            swap(s1[i], s1[i+1]);
        }
        
        for(int k=i+2;k<s1.length();k++){
            if(s1[k] == s2[j]){
                swap(s1[i], s2[k]);
                ans = min(ans,x + cost(s1, s2, i+1, j+1, x));
                swap(s1[i], s2[k]);
            }
        }
        cout<<ans<<",";
        return ans == INT_MAX ? -1 : ans;
    }
    
    
    int minOperations(string s1, string s2, int x) {
        return cost(s1, s2, 0, 0, x);
    }
};

[28/10/23, 8:22:22 PM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/number-of-islands/
[28/10/23, 8:22:29 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    vector<int> dx = {1,-1,0,0};
    vector<int> dy = {0,0,1,-1};

    void dfs_Helper(vector<vector<char>>& grid, int m, int n, int i, int j){
        //base case
        if(i == -1 || i == m || j == -1 || j == n){
            return;
        }

        if(grid[i][j] == '1'){
            grid[i][j] = '0';
            return;
        }

        if(grid[i][j] == '0'){
            return;
        }

        //recursive case
        for(int k=0;k<4;k++){
            dfs_Helper(grid, m, n, i+dx[k], j+dy[k]);
        }
    }

    int numIslands(vector<vector<char>>& grid) {
        int ans = 0;

        int m = grid.size();
        int n = grid[0].size();

        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                if(grid[i][j] == '1')[
                    dfs_Helper(grid, m, n, i, j);
                    ans++;
                ]
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
[28/10/23, 9:03:15 PM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/binary-tree-level-order-traversal-ii/
[28/10/23, 9:03:20 PM] Satvik Saini: /**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * struct TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode *left;
 *     TreeNode *right;
 *     TreeNode() : val(0), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
 *     TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
 *     TreeNode(int x, TreeNode *left, TreeNode *right) : val(x), left(left), right(right) {}
 * };
 */
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> levelOrderBottom(TreeNode* root) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        vector<int> row;

        queue<TreeNode*> q;
        q.push(root);
        q.push(NULL);

        while(!q.empty()){
            TreeNode* front = q.front();
            q.pop();

            if(front == NULL){
                ans.push_back(row);
                row.clear();
                if(!q.empty()){
                    q.push(NULL);
                }
            }
            else{
                row.push_back(front->val);
                if(front->left){
                    q.push(front->left);
                }
                if(front->right){
                    q.push(front->right);
                }
            }
        }
        reverse(ans.begin(), ans.end());
        return ans;
    }
};

[29/10/23, 1:03:02 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    int f(vector<int>& prices, int n, int i, int cnt, vector<vector<int>> &dp){
        //base case
        if(i == n || cnt == 2){
            return 0;
        }

        //lookup
        if(dp[i][cnt] != -1){
            return dp[i][cnt];
        }

        //recursive case

        //op1 : not buy
        int ans = f(prices, n, i+1, cnt, dp);

        for(int j=i+1;j<n;j++){
            if(prices[j] > prices[i])
            ans = max(ans, (prices[j] - prices[i]) + f(prices, n, j + 1, cnt + 1, dp));
        }

        return dp[i][cnt] = ans;
    }

    
    int maxProfit(vector<int>& prices) {
        int n = prices.size();

        vector<vector<int>> dp(n+1, vector<int>(2,-1));
        return f(prices, n, 0, 0, dp);
    }
};

[01/11/23, 2:12:26 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    int f(vector<int>& nums, unsigned int i, unsigned int j, unsigned int n){

        // base case
        if(i == j) return i == -1 || i == nums.size() ? 1 : nums[i];

        // recursive case
        int ans = INT_MIN;
        for(int k = i ; k <= j-1 ; k++){
            int z;
            if(k == -1) z =  nums[0] * nums[1];
            else if(k == n) z = nums[n-1] * nums[n-2];
            else z = nums[i]*nums[i-1]*nums[i+1];
            ans = max(ans,f(nums, i, k-1, n) + f(nums, k+1, j, n) + z) ;
        }
        return ans;

    }
    int maxCoins(vector<int>& nums) {
        return f(nums, 0, nums.size()-1, nums.size());        
    }
};

[04/11/23, 8:57:04 AM] Satvik Saini: class Graph {

public :

    unordered_map<char, list<char>> neighbourMap;

    Graph(unordered_set<char> vertexSet) {
        for (char vertex : vertexSet) {
            neighbourMap[vertex] = {};
        }
    }

    void addEdge(char u, char v) {
        // add a directed edge from 'u' to 'v'
        neighbourMap[u].push_back(v);
    }

    string topologicalSort() {

        unordered_map<char, int> inDegreeMap;
        for (pair<char, list<char>> vertex : neighbourMap) {
            list<char> neighbourList = vertex.second;
            for (char neighbour : neighbourList) {
                inDegreeMap[neighbour]++;
            }
        }

        queue<char> q;
        for (pair<char, list<char>> vertex : neighbourMap) {
            char vertexLabel = vertex.first;
            if (inDegreeMap.find(vertexLabel) == inDegreeMap.end()) {
                // vertex's inDegree is zero i.e. it has no dependecy
                q.push(vertexLabel);
            }
        }

        string uniqueString = "";

        while (!q.empty()) {
            char front = q.front(); q.pop();
            uniqueString += front;
            list<char> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
            for (char neighbour : neighbourList) {
                inDegreeMap[neighbour]--;
                if (inDegreeMap[neighbour] == 0) {
                    q.push(neighbour);
                }
            }
        }
        return uniqueString;
    }
};

class Solution {
public:

    string alienOrder(vector<string>& words) {

        int n = words.size();

        // handle incorrect input : ["abc","ab"] , here "abc" is not smaller than "ab" according to the alien language

        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
            string w1 = words[i];
            string w2 = words[i + 1];
            if (w1.size() > w2.size() && w1.substr(0, w2.size()) == w2) {
                return "";
            }
        }

        unordered_set<char> charSet;
        for (string word : words) {
            for (char ch : word) {
                charSet.insert(ch);
            }
        }

        Graph g(charSet);

        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
            string word1 = words[i];
            string word2 = words[i + 1];
            for (int j = 0; j < min(word1.size(), word2.size()); j++) {
                if (word1[j] != word2[j]) {
                    // word1[j] < word2[j] in the alien language i.e. word2[j] depends on word1[j]
                    g.addEdge(word1[j], word2[j]);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        string uniqueString = g.topologicalSort();

        return uniqueString.size() == charSet.size() ? uniqueString : "";
	  }
};

[05/11/23, 8:12:18 AM] Satvik Saini: template <typename T>
class edge {
	public :

		T u;
		T v;
		int w;

		edge(T u, T v, int w) {
			this->u = u;
			this->v = v;
			this->w = w;
		}
};

template <typename T>
class graph {

	set<T>  vertexSet;        // to store the graph representation
	vector<edge<T>> edgeList; // to store the graph representation

	public :

		void addEdge(T u, T v, int w) {
			// add an edge of weight 'w' b/w 'u' and 'v' 
			edgeList.push_back(edge<T>(u, v, w));
			vertexSet.insert(u);
			vertexSet.insert(v);
		}

		void bellmanFord(T s) {

			map<T, int> distMap; // to store a mapping b/w vertices and their
			                     // shortest distances from the source vertex
			for(T vertex: vertexSet) {
				distMap[vertex] = INT_MAX;
			}
			distMap[s] = 0;

			int V = vertexSet.size();
			for(int i=1; i<=V-1; i++) {
				for(edge<T> e : edgeList) {
					if(distMap[e.u] != INT_MAX && 
					   distMap[e.u]+e.w < distMap[e.v]) {
						// relax the edge from vertex u to v
						distMap[e.v] = distMap[e.u]+e.w;
					}
				}
			}

			for(edge<T> e : edgeList) {
				if(distMap[e.v] > distMap[e.u]+e.w) {
					// graph contains a negative weight cycle
					exit(0);
				}
			}

			for(pair<T, int> p : distMap) {
				cout << "(" << p.first << ", " << p.second << ")" << endl;
			}
		}
};

int main() {

	graph<char> g;

	g.addEdge('A', 'B', 1);
	g.addEdge('C', 'B', -3);
	g.addEdge('B', 'C', 2);

	g.bellmanFord('A');

	return 0;
}

[05/11/23, 1:55:36 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include<stdio.h>
#include<limits.h>
// #include<malloc.h>

struct node{
    int data;
    struct node* left;
    struct node* right;
};

struct node* createNode(int data){
    struct node *n; // creating a node pointer
    n = (struct node *) malloc(sizeof(struct node)); // Allocating memory in the heap
    n->data = data; // Setting the data
    n->left = NULL; // Setting the left and right children to NULL
    n->right = NULL; // Setting the left and right children to NULL
    return n; // Finally returning the created node
}

void preOrder(struct  node* root){
    if(root!=NULL){
        printf("%d ", root->data);
        preOrder(root->left);
        preOrder(root->right);
    }
}

void postOrder(struct  node* root){
    if(root!=NULL){
        postOrder(root->left);
        postOrder(root->right);
        printf("%d ", root->data);
    }
}

void inOrder(struct  node* root){
    if(root!=NULL){
        inOrder(root->left);
        printf("%d ", root->data);
        inOrder(root->right);
    }
}

int findmax(struct node* root){

    if(root == NULL) return INT_MIN;

    while( root->right != NULL){
        root = root->right;
    }
    return root->data;
}
int find_min(struct node* root){
    if(root == NULL) return INT_MAX;

    while(root->left != NULL){
        root = root->left;
    }
    return root->data;
}

int is_bst(struct node* root){

    // base case
    if(root == NULL){
        return 1;
    }
    // recursive case

    // check if given tree is bst 

    // recursively check if LST is BST 
    int leftbst = is_bst(root->left);
    // recursively check if rST is BST
    int rightbst = is_bst(root->right);

    // check if root is bst 
    return leftbst && rightbst && root->data > findmax(root->left) && root -> data < find_min(root->right); 

    
}
int bstrangeeff(struct node* root, long long lb, long long ub){

    // base case
    if(root == NULL){
        return 1;
    }

    // recursive case
    return bstrangeeff(root->left, lb, root->data) &&  bstrangeeff(root->right, root->data, ub) && root->data < ub && root -> data > lb;
}

struct node* insert_in_bst(struct node* root, int key){

    // base case
    if(root == NULL){
        return createNode(key);
    }

    // recursive case
    // insert 
    if(key < root -> data){
        // insert in LST 
        root->left = insert_in_bst(root -> left , key);
    }

    // insert in RST 
    root->right = insert_in_bst(root -> right , key);
    
    return root;

}
int search_in_bst(struct node* root, int key){

    // base case
    if(root == NULL) return 0;


    // recursive case
    if(root -> data == key) return 1;

    if(key > root->data){
        return search_in_bst(root->right, key);
    }
    return search_in_bst(root->left, key);

}
struct node* delete_bst(struct node* root, int k){

    // base case 
    if(root == NULL){
        // delete a node from an empty tree and return it 
        return NULL;
    }

    // recursive case
    if(root -> data < k){
        // delete key from LST
        root -> left = delete_bst(root,k);
    }
    else if( root -> data > k){
         // delete key from RST
        root -> right = delete_bst(root, k);
    }

    // delete the root node 
    // this will change the structure of the tree 
    // 1) leaf node 
    if(root -> right == NULL && root -> left == NULL){
        root = NULL;
    }
    // 2) single child node 
    else if(root -> right != NULL && root->left == NULL){
        root = root -> right
    }
    else if(root -> right == NULL && root->left != NULL){
        root = root -> left;
    }
    // 3) two child
    else{
        struct node* lstmax = findmax(root);  
        swap(root->data , lstmax -> data);
        root -> left = delete_bst(root->left, k);

    }
    return root;
    

}
int main(){
     
    // Constructing the root node - Using Function (Recommended)
    struct node *p = createNode(5);
    struct node *p1 = createNode(3);
    struct node *p2 = createNode(6);
    struct node *p3 = createNode(1);
    struct node *p4 = createNode(4);
    // Finally The tree looks like this:
    //      5
    //     / \
    //    3   6
    //   / \
    //  1   4  

    // Linking the root node with left and right children
    p->left = p1;
    p->right = p2;
    p1->left = p3;
    p1->right = p4;

    // preOrder(p);
    // printf("\n");
    // postOrder(p); 
    // printf("\n");
    inOrder(p);
    printf("\n");
    // printf("%d", isBST(p)); 
    if(bstrangeeff(p, INT_MIN, INT_MAX)){
        printf("This is a bst" );
    }
    else{
        printf("This is not a bst");
    }
    return 0;
}

[05/11/23, 2:00:56 PM] Satvik Saini: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

#define max(a, b) ((a) > (b) ? (a) : (b))

struct TreeNode {
    int val;
    struct TreeNode* left;
    struct TreeNode* right;
};

struct TreeNode* buildTree() {

	int data;
	scanf("%d", &data);

	// base case

	if (data == -1) {
		return NULL;
	}

	// recursive case
	struct TreeNode* root = (struct TreeNode*)malloc(sizeof(struct TreeNode));
    root->val = data;

	// 1. ask your friend to build the leftSubtree using the preOrder traversal of the leftSubtree
	root->left = buildTree();

	// 2. ask your friend to build the rightSubtree using the preOrder traversal of the rightSubtree
	root->right = buildTree();

	return root;

}

// struct TreeNode* createNode(int val) {
//     struct TreeNode* newNode = (struct TreeNode*)malloc(sizeof(struct TreeNode));
//     newNode->val = val;
//     newNode->left = newNode->right = NULL;
//     return newNode;
// }

int height(struct TreeNode* root) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        return 0;
    }

    int leftHeight = height(root->left);
    int rightHeight = height(root->right);

    return 1 + max(leftHeight, rightHeight);
}

// Function to compute the diameter of a binary tree
int diameter(struct TreeNode* root) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        return 0;
    }

    int op1 = diameter(root->left);
    int op2 = diameter(root->right);
    int op3 = height(root->left) + height(root->right) + 1;

    return max(op1, max(op2, op3));
}

// Function for level-order traversal of a binary tree
void levelOrderTraversal(struct TreeNode* root) {
    if (root == NULL) return;

    struct TreeNode* queue[100]; // Assuming a maximum of 100 nodes in the tree
    int front = 0, rear = 0;

    queue[rear++] = root;

    while (front < rear) {
        struct TreeNode* current = queue[front++];
        printf("%d ", current->val);

        if (current->left) queue[rear++] = current->left;
        if (current->right) queue[rear++] = current->right;
    }
}

void inorderTraversal(struct TreeNode* root) {
    if (root == NULL) return;

    inorderTraversal(root->left);
    printf("%d ", root->val);
    inorderTraversal(root->right);
}

void preorderTraversal(struct TreeNode* root) {
    if (root == NULL) return;

    printf("%d ", root->val);
    preorderTraversal(root->left);
    preorderTraversal(root->right);
}

void postorderTraversal(struct TreeNode* root) {
    if (root == NULL) return;

    postorderTraversal(root->left);
    postorderTraversal(root->right);
    printf("%d ", root->val);
}

int main() {

    struct TreeNode* root = buildTree();

    printf("Level-Order Traversal: ");
    levelOrderTraversal(root);
    printf("\n");

    printf("Inorder Traversal: ");
    inorderTraversal(root);
    printf("\n");

    printf("Preorder Traversal: ");
    preorderTraversal(root);
    printf("\n");

    printf("Postorder Traversal: ");
    postorderTraversal(root);
    printf("\n");

    printf("Height of the tree: %d\n", height(root));
    printf("Diameter of the tree: %d\n", diameter(root));

    return 0;
}
[05/11/23, 2:01:03 PM] Satvik Saini: bst
[05/11/23, 2:01:04 PM] Satvik Saini: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <limits.h>

struct TreeNode {
    int val;
    struct TreeNode *left;
    struct TreeNode *right;
};

// Function to create a new node
struct TreeNode *createNode(int value) {
    struct TreeNode *newNode = (struct TreeNode*)malloc(sizeof(struct TreeNode));
    newNode->val = value;
    newNode->left = newNode->right = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

// Function to insert a value into the BST
struct TreeNode *insert(struct TreeNode *root, int value) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        return createNode(value);
    }
    if (value < root->val) {
        root->left = insert(root->left, value);
    } else if (value > root->val) {
        root->right = insert(root->right, value);
    }
    return root;
}

// Function to find the minimum element in the BST
int findMin(struct TreeNode *root) {
    while (root->left != NULL) {
        root = root->left;
    }
    return root->val;
}

// Function to find the maximum element in the BST
int findMax(struct TreeNode *root) {
    while (root->right != NULL) {
        root = root->right;
    }
    return root->val;
}

// Function to delete a value from the BST
struct TreeNode *delete(struct TreeNode *root, int value) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        return root;
    }
    if (value < root->val) {
        root->left = delete(root->left, value);
    } else if (value > root->val) {
        root->right = delete(root->right, value);
    } else {
        // Node with only one child or no child
        if (root->left == NULL) {
            struct TreeNode *temp = root->right;
            free(root);
            return temp;
        } else if (root->right == NULL) {
            struct TreeNode *temp = root->left;
            free(root);
            return temp;
        }

        // Node with two children: Get the in-order successor (smallest in the right subtree)
        root->val = findMin(root->right);

        // Delete the in-order successor
        root->right = delete(root->right, root->val);
    }
    return root;
}

struct TreeNode* search(struct TreeNode* root, int key) {
    if (root == NULL || root->val == key) {
        return root;
    }

    if (key < root->val) {
        return search(root->left, key);
    } else {
        return search(root->right, key);
    }
}

// Function to validate if the tree is a BST
int isBST(struct TreeNode *root, int min, int max) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        return 1;
    }
    if (root->val < min || root->val > max) {
        return 0;
    }
    return isBST(root->left, min, root->val - 1) && isBST(root->right, root->val + 1, max);
}

int main() {
    struct TreeNode *root = NULL;

    // Insert elements into the BST
    root = insert(root, 50);
    root = insert(root, 30);
    root = insert(root, 20);
    root = insert(root, 40);
    root = insert(root, 70);
    root = insert(root, 60);
    root = insert(root, 80);

    // Find minimum and maximum elements
    printf("Minimum element: %d\n", findMin(root));
    printf("Maximum element: %d\n", findMax(root));

    // Delete an element
    root = delete(root, 30);

    int key = 60;
    struct TreeNode* result = search(root, key);

    if (result != NULL) {
        printf("%d found in the BST.\n", key);
    } else {
        printf("%d not found in the BST.\n", key);
    }

    // Check if it's a valid BST
    if (isBST(root, INT_MIN, INT_MAX)) {
        printf("It's a valid BST.\n");
    }
    else {
        printf("It's not a valid BST.\n");
    }

    return 0;
}

    bool hasPathSum(TreeNode* root, int targetSum) {

            if(root -> val == targetSum) return true;
            return false;
        }

        // recursive case

    }

[06/11/23, 7:20:20 AM] Satvik Saini: vector<int> asteroidCollision(vector<int>& asteroids) {

	stack<int> s;

	for (int ast : asteroids) {
		if (ast < 0 and !s.empty() and s.top() > 0) {
			// there will be a collision
			bool flag = true; // assume 'ast' will destroy all the positive asteroids

			while (!s.empty() and s.top() > 0) {

				if (abs(ast) == s.top()) {
					// 'ast' and s.top() will be destroyed
					flag = false;
					s.pop();
					break;
				} 
				else if (abs(ast) < s.top()) {
					// 'ast' will be destroyed
					flag = false;
					break;
				} 
				else {
					// s.top() will be destroyed
					s.pop();
				}
			}

			if (flag == true) {
			// 'ast' has destroyed all the positive asteroids on the top of the stack
				s.push(ast);
			}
		} 
    else {
			s.push(ast);
		}
	}

	vector<int> out;

	while (!s.empty()) {
		out.push_back(s.top());
		s.pop();
	}

	reverse(out.begin(), out.end());

	return out;

}

int main() {

	vector<int> asteroids = {7, 3, -4, 5, 2, -8, 2, 4, 1, -4};

	vector<int> out = asteroidCollision(asteroids);

	for (int i = 0; i < out.size(); i++) {

		cout << out[i] << " ";

	}

	cout << endl;

	return 0;
}

[07/11/23, 6:47:03 PM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-increasing-path-in-a-matrix/
[07/11/23, 6:47:08 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> dx = {0,0,1,-1};
    vector<int> dy = {1,-1,0,0};
    int f(vector<vector<int>>& matrix, int m, int n, int i, int j, vector<vector<int>> &dp){
    
        if(dp[i][j] != -1) return dp[i][j];

        int cnt = 1;
        for(int k=0;k<4;k++){
            int ii = i + dx[k];
            int jj = j + dy[k];

            if(ii >=0 && ii < m && jj >= 0 && jj < m && matrix[ii][jj] > matrix[i][j]){
                cnt = max(cnt, 1 + f(matrix, m, n, ii, jj, dp));
            }
        }

        return dp[i][j] = cnt;

    }

    int longestIncreasingPath(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {

        int ans = 0;
        int m = matrix.size();
        int n = matrix[0].size();

        vector<vector<int>> dp(m, vector<int>(n, -1));

        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                ans = max(ans, f(matrix, m, n, i, j, dp));
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

[09/11/23, 12:45:17 PM] Satvik Saini: Longest Window of Sum K
[09/11/23, 12:46:29 PM] Satvik Saini: int main(){

    int arr[] = {2, 3, 2, 4, 0, 2, 0};
    int n = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(int);
    int k = 6;

    int i = 0; // to store the start of the window
    int j = 0; // to store the end of the window

    int w_sum = 0; // to store the window sum

    int max_len = 0; // to track the length of the longest
    // window which has a sum equals to k

    int best_i;
    int best_j;

    // time : O(n)
    // space : O(1)

    while (j < n){

        // expand the window
        // add arr[j] to the window

        w_sum += arr[j];

        // check for the violation of the window property

        while (w_sum > k)
        {
            // window property is violated, fix it by shrinking the window
            // remove the ith element from the window

            w_sum -= arr[i];
            i++;
        }

        // check for the validity of the window, and update the answer

        if (w_sum == k)
        {

            // you've found a valid window

            // max_len = max(max_len, j - i + 1);

            if (j - i + 1 > max_len){
                max_len = j - i + 1;
                best_i = i;
                best_j = j;
            }
        }

        // continue expansion of the window
        j++;
    }

    // cout << best_i << " " << best_j << endl;
    for (int i = best_i; i <= best_j; i++){
        cout << arr[i] << " ";
    }

    cout << endl;
    cout << max_len << endl;

    return 0;
}

[28/11/23, 2:10:16 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <iostream>

// Class template definition
template <typename T>
class MyClassTemplate {
public:
    T data;

    // Constructor
    MyClassTemplate(const T& value) : data(value) {}

    // Member function to display data
    void display() const {
        std::cout << "Data: " << data << std::endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    // Instantiation of the class template with int as the template argument
    MyClassTemplate<int> intInstance(42);

    // Displaying data of the instantiated template class
    std::cout << "Instantiated Template Class with int:" << std::endl;
    intInstance.display();

    // Instantiation of the class template with double as the template argument
    MyClassTemplate<double> doubleInstance(3.14);

    // Displaying data of the instantiated template class
    std::cout << "\nInstantiated Template Class with double:" << std::endl;
    doubleInstance.display();

    return 0;
}

}
[28/11/23, 2:37:58 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: The procedure behind choosing the correct overloaded function involves a combination of template argument deduction and function overload resolution. Let's break down the steps:

1. **Function Overload Resolution:**
   - The compiler first considers all the overloaded functions that match the name `display` in the scope.
   - It checks for an exact match based on the argument types.
   - If there is an exact match, that function is chosen.
   - If there is no exact match, the compiler considers template functions.

2. **Template Argument Deduction:**
   - For template functions, the compiler tries to deduce the template arguments based on the provided function arguments.
   - It considers both template functions and non-template functions during this phase.
  
3. **Selection Criteria:**
   - If there's a non-template function that is an exact match, it is preferred over template functions.
   - If there's more than one template function that could match, the compiler considers the best match based on template argument deduction.
   - If a template function is a viable match, it is selected.

Now, let's apply these steps to each case in the provided code:

1. **`display(100)`:**
   - The argument is of type `int`.
   - There is a non-template function that is an exact match (`void display(int x)`).
   - Therefore, the non-template function is chosen.

2. **`display(12.34)`:**
   - The argument is of type `double`.
   - There is a template function that can accept any type (`template <class T> void display(T x)`).
   - The template function is a better match because it can handle any type, including `double`.
   - Therefore, the template function is chosen.

3. **`display('C')`:**
   - The argument is of type `char`.
   - There is a non-template function that is an exact match (`void display(int x)`).
   - Therefore, the non-template function is chosen.

In summary, the procedure involves considering both non-template functions and template functions during the overload resolution process. The compiler chooses the function that best matches the provided arguments, giving preference to non-template functions when they are an exact match.

[28/11/23, 6:38:18 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: In a programming environment, function calls and parameter passing are closely related to the concept of a stack. The call stack, also known as the execution stack or runtime stack, is a data structure used to manage the execution flow of a program. It plays a crucial role in implementing function calls and managing parameters. Let's analyze how a stack is used in these scenarios:

### Function Calls:

1. **Function Call Activation:**
   - When a function is called, a new frame (activation record or stack frame) is created on the call stack to store information about the function call.
   - The frame includes the return address, local variables, and other information needed for the execution of the function.

2. **Pushing onto the Stack:**
   - The new frame is pushed onto the top of the stack.
   - This allows the program to keep track of the active function calls, as the top of the stack represents the current point of execution.

3. **Control Flow:**
   - The control flow transfers to the called function, and it starts executing from its entry point.

4. **Return Address:**
   - The return address (the address to resume execution after the function completes) is stored in the current frame.

5. **Local Variables:**
   - Local variables of the function are allocated space within the frame.

6. **Recursion:**
   - For recursive function calls, multiple instances of the same function can be on the stack simultaneously, each with its own set of local variables and return address.

7. **Popping from the Stack:**
   - When a function completes its execution, its frame is popped off the stack, and control returns to the calling function using the stored return address.

### Parameter Passing:

1. **Parameter Storage:**
   - Function parameters are typically passed using the stack.
   - The caller pushes the parameters onto the stack before making the function call.

2. **Parameter Order:**
   - The order in which parameters are pushed onto the stack is determined by the calling convention, which is a set of rules that specifies how functions receive parameters and return values.

3. **Caller Responsibilities:**
   - The calling function is responsible for preparing the stack with the necessary parameters before making the call.

4. **Callee Responsibilities:**
   - The called function retrieves its parameters from the stack, performs its operations, and places the return value (if any) on the stack before returning.

### Example:

Consider the following C++ code:

```cpp
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    int result = add(3, 4);
    return 0;
}
```

1. **Function Call:**
   - `main` calls the `add` function.
   - The call stack looks like:
     ```
     +-------------------------+
     | add Frame               |
     |-------------------------|
     | return address         | <-- main's return address
     | a (parameter)          | <-- 3
     | b (parameter)          | <-- 4
     +-------------------------+
     | main Frame              |
     |-------------------------|
     | ... (main's variables) |
     +-------------------------+
     ```

2. **Execution:**
   - `add` executes, and the result is stored in its frame.

3. **Return:**
   - `add` returns, and its frame is popped off the stack.
   - Control returns to `main` at the stored return address.

4. **Final Stack:**
   ```
   +-------------------------+
   | main Frame              |
   |-------------------------|
   | ... (main's variables) |
   +-------------------------+
   ```

In summary, the call stack provides a structured way to manage function calls and parameter passing. It ensures proper execution flow, maintains the state of each function call, and allows for recursion. The stack is a fundamental part of the runtime environment for many programming languages.
[28/11/23, 6:39:21 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: Certainly! Let's break it down in simpler terms:

### Function Calls:

1. **Starting a Function:**
   - When a function is called, a special memory area called the stack is used.
   - Think of the stack like a stack of plates. Each plate represents a function call.

2. **Stack Frames:**
   - A stack frame is like a plate. It holds information about the function call, like variables and where to go back when done.
   - When a function is called, a new plate (stack frame) is added to the top of the stack.

3. **Doing the Work:**
   - The function starts working. If it calls another function, another plate is added on top for that function.

4. **Returning:**
   - When a function finishes, its plate is taken off the top, and we go back to the previous function.

### Parameter Passing:

1. **Passing Information:**
   - When you call a function, you often want to give it some information (parameters).
   - These parameters are placed on the top plate of the stack.

2. **Getting Information:**
   - The function takes its parameters from the top plate to use them.
   - After finishing, the parameters are removed with the plate.

### Example:

1. **Calling a Function:**
   - Imagine you have a function `add(3, 4)` in your code.
   - When you call it, a new plate is added to the stack for the `add` function.

2. **Working:**
   - The `add` function does its job (adds 3 and 4), and its plate stays on the stack.

3. **Returning:**
   - After finishing, the `add` plate is taken off, and we go back to where we called it.

4. **Final Result:**
   - The stack now only has the plate for the function that called `add`.

In short, the stack helps keep track of where the program is, manages function calls, and passes information between functions using plates (stack frames). It's like a stack of trays in a cafeteria - you take a tray to get your food (function call), do your eating (function execution), and then return the tray (function return).

[01/12/23, 12:57:16 PM] Satvik Saini: Certainly! Utilitarianism is an ethical theory that suggests that the best action is the one that maximizes overall happiness or pleasure. It focuses on the consequences of actions and aims to achieve the greatest good for the greatest number of people. Here's a simple explanation of Utilitarianism in tabular format:

| **Aspect**                 | **Description**                                                                              |
|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Core Principle**         | The morality of an action is determined by its overall impact on maximizing happiness or pleasure.  |
| **Focus**                  | Consequences of actions are crucial; the ends justify the means.                               |
| **Goal**                   | Maximize overall happiness or pleasure for the greatest number of people.                      |
| **Evaluation Criteria**   | Compare outcomes based on the net balance of pleasure over pain.                                |
| **Quantitative Approach**  | Happiness is often quantified, and actions are assessed based on the greatest overall happiness. |
| **Impartiality**          | All individuals are considered equal; no one's happiness is prioritized over another's.         |
| **Decision-Making**       | Choose actions that lead to the greatest overall happiness and minimize pain.                   |
| **Flexibility**           | Adaptable to various situations; actions may differ based on circumstances.                    |
| **Critiques**             | - Difficulty in quantifying happiness. <br> - Challenges in predicting long-term consequences.  <br> - Potential for sacrificing individual rights. |
| **Examples**              | - Providing healthcare for all citizens. <br> - Environmental conservation for future generations. <br> - Utilizing resources to maximize societal welfare. |

**Summary:**
Utilitarianism is an ethical theory that emphasizes maximizing overall happiness or pleasure as the ultimate goal. It evaluates actions based on their consequences, prioritizing the greatest good for the greatest number of people. While it provides a straightforward approach to decision-making, it faces challenges in quantifying happiness and predicting long-term consequences. Examples of utilitarian thinking include policies that promote social welfare and environmental conservation.

[21/12/23, 11:15:43 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:

    bool dfs_helper(vector<int>& colorMap, int source, int color, vector<vector<int>>& graph){
        // visit the source node 
        colorMap[source] = color;
        vector<int> neighbourList = graph[source];
        for( int neighbour : neighbourList){
            if(colorMap[neighbour] == -1){
                if(dfs_helper(colorMap, neighbour, abs(color-1), graph)) return true;
            }else{
                if(colorMap[neighbour] == colorMap[source]) return false;
            }
        }
        return true;

    }
    bool isBipartite(vector<vector<int>>& graph) {
        int n = graph.size();
        vector<int> colorMap(-1,n);
        for( int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
            if(dfs_helper(colorMap, i, 1, graph))  return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
    
};
[21/12/23, 11:19:14 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: }

	bool bfsHelper(T source, unordered_map<T, int>& colorMap) {

		queue<T> q; // to keep track of unexplored & colored vertices

		// color the 'source' vertex
		colorMap[source] = 0;
		q.push(source);

		while (!q.empty()) {
			T front = q.front();
			q.pop();

			// explore 'front'

			list<T> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
			for (T neighbour : neighbourList) {
				if (colorMap.find(neighbour) == colorMap.end()) {
					// neighbour is not yet colored / visited
					colorMap[neighbour] = 1 - colorMap[front];
					q.push(neighbour);
				} else {
					// neighbour is already colored / visited
					if (colorMap[front] == colorMap[neighbour]) {
						return false;
					}
				}
			}
		}

		return true;

	}

[22/12/23, 9:40:53 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    bool dfs_helper(int n, vector<vector<int>>& graph, int source, int destination, vector<int>& visited){
        visited[source] = 1;
        if(source == destination) {
            cout<<source<<endl;
            return true;
        }
        for(int neighbour : graph[source]){
            if(!visited[neighbour]){
                return dfs_helper(n,graph,neighbour,destination,visited);
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
    bool validPath(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges, int source, int destination) {
        vector<int> visited(n, 0);
        vector<vector<int>>graph(n);
        for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
            int v = edges[i][0];
            int u =edges[i][1];
            graph[v].push_back(u);
            graph[u].push_back(v);

        }
        return dfs_helper(n,graph,source,destination,visited);
    }
};

[23/12/23, 8:28:14 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    bool solve(int n,int m,int i,int j,vector<vector<char>>& board, string word,int k){

        //base case

        if(k == word.length()) return true;

        if(i == -1 || i == n || j == -1 || j == m || word[k] != board[i][j]) return false;

        //recursive case

        board[i][j] = '.';
       
        int dx[] = {0, 0, 1, -1};
        int dy[] = {1, -1, 0, 0};

        for(int l=0;l<4;l++){
            if(solve(n, m, i + dx[l], j + dy[l], board, word, k + 1)) return true;
        }
        board[i][j] = word[k];
        return false;
    }

    bool exist(vector<vector<char>>& board, string word) {
        if(!word.length()) return false;
        int n=board.size();
        int m=board[0].size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<m;j++){
                if(board[i][j] == word[0]){
                    if(solve(n, m, i, j, board, word, 0)) return true;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }


    vector<string> findWords(vector<vector<char>>& board, vector<string>& words) {
        vector<string> ans;
        for(string s : words){
            if(exist(board, s)){
                ans.push_back(s);
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

[23/12/23, 6:14:11 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:
    bool isHappy(int n) {
        unordered_set<int> visited;
        visited.insert(n);

        while(n != 1){
            int num = 0;
            while(n){
                num += pow(n%10, 2);
                n /= 10;
            }
            n = num;
            if(visited.find(n) != visited.end()){
                break;
            }
        }
        return n == 1;
    }
};

[25/12/23, 1:23:32 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: int scoreOfParentheses(string s) {
        stack<int> stk;
        for(char c : s){
            
            if(c == '('){
                stk.push(-1);
            }
            else{
                // calculate result
                int sum = 0;
                stk.pop();
                while(stk.top()!=-1){
                    sum+=stk.top();
                    stk.pop();
                }
                sum = max(2*sum , 1);
                stk.pop();
                stk.push(2*sum);
            }
        }
        int count = 0;
        while(!stk.empty()){
            count+=stk.top();
            stk.pop();
        }
        return count;
    }

[26/12/23, 8:27:49 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    int f(int n, int k, int target, int j, vector<int> dp){
        // lookup 
        if(dp[j] != -1){
            return dp[j];
        }
        // base case
        if(j == n){
            return 0;
        }
        // recursive case
        int count = 0;
        for(int i=1 ; i<=k ; i++){
            if(target - i >= 0 ){
                count += 1 + f(n,k,target-i,j+1,dp);
            }
        }
        return dp[j] = count;

    }
    int numRollsToTarget(int n, int k, int target) {
        vector<int> dp(n,-1);
        return f(n,k,target,0,dp);
        
    }
};

[26/12/23, 9:04:25 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    int f(int n, int k, int target, vector<int> &dp){
        //base case
        if(n == 0){
            if(target == 0){
                return 1;
            }
            return 0;
        }

        //lookup


        //recursive case
        int count = 0;
        for(int i=1;i<=k;i++){
            if(i <= target){
                count += numRollsToTarget(n - 1, k, target - i);
            }
        }
        return count;
    }

    int numRollsToTarget(int n, int k, int target) {
        return f(n, k, target, dp);
    }
};
[26/12/23, 9:09:35 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: ‎This message was deleted.
[26/12/23, 9:13:46 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    int f(int n, int k, int target, vector<vector<int>> &dp){
        //base case
        if(n == 0){
            if(target == 0){
                return 1;
            }
            return 0;
        }

        //lookup
        if(dp[n][target] != -1){
            return dp[n][target];
        }

        //recursive case
        int count = 0;
        for(int i=1;i<=k;i++){
            if(i <= target){
                count += f(n - 1, k, target - i, dp);
            }
        }
        return dp[n][target] = count;
    }

    int numRollsToTarget(int n, int k, int target) {
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(target, -1));
        return f(n, k, target, dp);
    }
};

[26/12/23, 12:22:51 PM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    bool f(vector<int>& nums, int p1, int p2, bool p1_turn){
        // base case
        if(nums.size() == 0){
            return p1 >= p2;
        }  

        // recursive case

        if(p1_turn){
            if(nums[0] > nums[nums.size() - 1]){
                vector<int> new_nums(nums.begin() + 1, nums.end());
                return f(new_nums, p1 + nums[0], p2, !p1_turn);
            }
            else{
                vector<int> new_nums(nums.begin(), nums.end() - 1);
                return f(new_nums, p1 + nums[nums.size() - 1], p2, !p1_turn);
            }
        }
        else{
            if(nums[0] > nums[nums.size() - 1]){
                vector<int> new_nums(nums.begin() + 1, nums.end());
                return f(new_nums, p1, p2 + nums[0], !p1_turn);
            }
            else{
                vector<int> new_nums(nums.begin(), nums.end() - 1);
                return f(new_nums, p1, p2 + nums[nums.size() - 1], !p1_turn);
            }
        }
    }

    bool predictTheWinner(vector<int>& nums) {
       return f(nums, 0, 0, true);
    }
};

[28/12/23, 7:59:21 AM] Satvik Saini: int editDistanceTopDown(string s1, string s2, int m, int n, int i, int j, vector<vector<int>> &dp)
{
    // base case
    if (i == m){
        return j - n;
    }
    if (j == n){
        return i - m;
    }

    //lookup
    if(dp[i][j] != -1){
        return dp[i][j];
    }

    // recursive case

    int X = editDistanceTopDown(s1, s2, m, n, i + 1, j, dp);
    int Y = editDistanceTopDown(s1, s2, m, n, i, j + 1, dp);
    int Z = editDistanceTopDown(s1, s2, m, n, i + 1, j + 1, dp);

    return dp[i][j] = min({X + 1, Y + 1, (int)(s1[i] != s2[j]) + Z});
}

[28/12/23, 11:53:31 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    int f(int n, string s, int i, vector<int> &dp){
        //base case
        if(n == 0){
            return 1;
        }

        //lookup
        if(dp[i] != -1){
            return dp[i];
        }

        //recursive case
        int count = 0;
        string str = "";
        for(int j=i;j<s.length();j++){
            str += s[j];
            count += f(n - 1, s, j, dp);
        }

        return dp[i] = count;
    }

    int countVowelStrings(int n) {
        string s = "aeiou";
        vector<int> dp(n+1, -1);
        return f(n, s, 0, dp);
    }
};

[29/12/23, 10:39:15 AM] Satvik Saini: class graph{
    unordered_map<int, list<int>> neighbourMap;
public:
    void addEdge(int u, int v){
        neighbourMap[u].push_back(v);
    }

    void bfs_helper(int source, unordered_set<int> &visited, unordered_map<int,int> &outDeg){
        visited.insert(source);
        queue<int> q;
        q.push(source);

        while(!q.empty()){

            int front = q.front();
            q.pop();

            list<int> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
            for(int neighbour : neighbourList){
                cout<<"increment"<<" ";
                outDeg[front]++;
                if(visited.find(neighbour) == visited.end()){
                    q.push(neighbour);
                    visited.insert(neighbour);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    void outDegreePop(unordered_map<int,int> &outDeg){
        unordered_set<int> visited;
        for(pair<int,list<int>> neighbourPair : neighbourMap){
            int vertex = neighbourPair.first;
            if(visited.find(vertex) != visited.end()){
                bfs_helper(vertex, visited, outDeg);
            }
        }
    }
};

class Solution {
public:
    int findJudge(int n, vector<vector<int>>& trust) {
        graph g;

        for(int i=0;i<trust.size();i++){
            g.addEdge(trust[i][0], trust[i][1]);
        }

        unordered_map<int,int> outDeg;
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            outDeg[i] = 0;
        }
        g.outDegreePop(outDeg);

        for(pair<int,int> Pair : outDeg){
            cout<<"element : "<<Pair.first<<" outdeg : "<<Pair.second<<endl;
            // if(Pair.second == 0){
            //     return Pair.first;
            // }
        }

        return -1;
    }
};

[29/12/23, 12:15:08 PM] Satvik Saini: class graph{
    unordered_map<int, list<int>> neighbourMap;
public:
    void addEdge(int u, int v){
        neighbourMap[u].push_back(v);
        neighbourMap[v].push_back(u);
    }

    int maxDist(int source, unordered_set<int> &visited, int n){
        visited.insert(source);
        unordered_map<int,int> DistMap;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            DistMap[i] = 0;
        }
        // DistMap[source] = 0;
        queue<int> q;
        q.push(source);

        while(!q.empty()){

            int front = q.front();
            q.pop();

            list<int> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
            for(int neighbour : neighbourList){
                if(visited.find(neighbour) == visited.end()){
                    DistMap[neighbour] = 1 + DistMap[front];
                    q.push(neighbour);
                    visited.insert(neighbour);
                }
            }
        }

        int height = 0;

        for(pair<int,int> P : DistMap){
            height = max(height, P.second);
        }

        return height;
    }
};


class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findMinHeightTrees(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        vector<int> ans;

        graph g;

        for(int i=0;i<edges.size();i++){
            g.addEdge(edges[i][0], edges[i][1]);
        }

        int min_height = INT_MAX;
        unordered_set<int> visited;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(min_height > g.maxDist(i, visited, n)){
                min_height = g.maxDist(i, visited, n);
                ans.clear();
                ans.push_back(i);
            }
            else if(min_height == g.maxDist(i, visited, n)){
                ans.push_back(i);
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
[29/12/23, 12:25:07 PM] Satvik Saini: class graph{
    unordered_map<int, list<int>> neighbourMap;

        neighbourMap[v].push_back(u);
    }

    int maxDist(int source, int n){
        unordered_set<int> visited;
        visited.insert(source);
        unordered_map<int,int> DistMap;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            DistMap[i] = 0;
        }
        // DistMap[source] = 0;
        queue<int> q;
        q.push(source);

        while(!q.empty()){

            int front = q.front();
            q.pop();

            list<int> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
            for(int neighbour : neighbourList){
                if(visited.find(neighbour) == visited.end()){
                    DistMap[neighbour] = 1 + DistMap[front];
                    q.push(neighbour);
                    visited.insert(neighbour);
                }
            }
        }

        int height = 0;

        for(pair<int,int> P : DistMap){
            height = max(height, P.second);
        }

        return height;
    }
};

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findMinHeightTrees(int n, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        vector<int> ans;

        graph g;

        for(int i=0;i<edges.size();i++){
            g.addEdge(edges[i][0], edges[i][1]);
        }

        int min_height = INT_MAX;

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            int height = g.maxDist(i, n);
            if(min_height > height){
                min_height = height;
                ans.clear();
                ans.push_back(i);
            }
            else if(min_height == height){
                ans.push_back(i);
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

[30/12/23, 8:37:19 AM] Satvik Saini: https://leetcode.com/problems/number-of-provinces/description/
[30/12/23, 8:37:23 AM] Satvik Saini: class graph{
    unordered_map<int, list<int>> neighbourMap;
public:
    graph(unordered_set<int> numSet){
        for(int ele : numSet){
            neighbourMap[ele] = {};
        }
    }

    void addEdge(int u, int v){
        neighbourMap[u].push_back(v);
        neighbourMap[v].push_back(u);
    }

    void bfs_helper(int source, unordered_set<int> &visited){
        visited.insert(source);
        queue<int> q;
        q.push(source);

        while(!q.empty()){

            int front = q.front();
            q.pop();

            list<int> neighbourList = neighbourMap[front];
            for(int neighbour : neighbourList){
                if(visited.find(neighbour) == visited.end()){
                    q.push(neighbour);
                    visited.insert(neighbour);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    int bfs(){
        int count = 0;
        unordered_set<int> visited;
        for(pair<int,list<int>> neighbourPair : neighbourMap){
            int vertex = neighbourPair.first;
            if(visited.find(vertex) != visited.end()){
                count++;
                bfs_helper(vertex, visited);
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
};

class Solution {
public:
    int findCircleNum(vector<vector<int>>& isConnected) {

        unordered_set<int> numSet;
        for(int i=0;i<isConnected.size();i++){
            numSet.insert(i);
        }

        graph g(numSet);

        for(int i=0;i<isConnected.size();i++){
            for(int j=i+1;j<isConnected.size();j++){
                if(isConnected[i][j] == 1){
                    g.addEdge(i, j);
                }
            }
        }

        return g.bfs();
    }
};

[31/12/23, 9:52:20 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
   int countSubstring(string& txt, string& pat)
{
    int M = pat.length();
    int N = txt.length();
    int res = 0;
 
    
    for (int i = 0; i <= N - M; i++) {

        for (int j = 0; j < M; j++)
            if (txt[i + j] != pat[j])
                break;
 
       
        if (j == M) {
            res++;
        }
    }
    return res;
}
 
    bool isspecial(string s ){
        for(int i=1 ; i<s.size() ; i++){
            if(s[i] != s[i-1]) return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
    int maximumLength(string s) {
        map<string,int> mpp;
       int i = 1;
        mpp[string(1,s[0])] = 1; 
        while(i < s.size()){
            int count = 1;
            int k = i;
            if(s[k]  != s[k-1]){
                mpp[s.substr(k,1)];
            }
            while(s[k] == s[k-1]){
                count ++;
                mpp[s.substr(i-1,count)] = count;
                cout<<s.substr(i-1,count)<<" ";
                k++;
            }
     
            i++;
        }
        int maxi = 0;
        for(pair<string , int> p : mpp){
            p.second = countSubstring(s,p.first);
             // cout<<p.first<<" "<<p.second<<endl;
            if(p.second  >= 3){
             maxi = max((int)p.first.size(), maxi);   
                // cout<<maxi<<" ";
            }
        }
        

        return maxi == 0 ? -1 : maxi;
        
        
    }
};
[31/12/23, 10:00:43 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    
    void result(string s, int n, vector<string>&vs)
    {
        unordered_set<string> st;

        for (int i = 0; i < (int)s.size(); i++) {

            string ans = "";
            for (int j = i; j < (int)s.size(); j++) {
                if(j>0)
                {
                    if(s[j] != s[j-1])
                        break;
                }
                ans += s[j];

                if (ans.size() == n) {

                    st.insert(ans);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        for (auto it : st)
            vs.push_back(it);
    }
    
    int countFreq(string& pat, string& txt)
    {
        int M = pat.length();
        int N = txt.length();
        int res = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i <= N - M; i++) {
            int j;
            for (j = 0; j < M; j++)
                if (txt[i + j] != pat[j])
                    break;

            if (j == M) {
                res++;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
    
    int maximumLength(string s) {
        vector<string>vs;
        map<string, int>mp;
        
        int n = s.length();
        for(int i = 1; i<(n); i++)
        {
            result(s, i, vs);
        }
        
        n = vs.size();
        int maxi = 0;
        for(int i = n-1; i>=0; i--)
        {
            set<char>st;
            for(auto i: vs[i])
            {            
                st.insert(i);
            }
            if(st.size() == 1)
            {
                int x = countFreq(vs[i], s);
                if(x>=3)
                {
                    int a =vs[i].length();
                    maxi = max(maxi, a);
                }    
            }
        }
        if(maxi == 0)
            return -1;
        return maxi;
    }
};

[01/01/24, 10:12:40 AM] Satvik Saini: class Solution {
public:

    vector<int> dx = {0, 0, 1, -1};
    vector<int> dy = {1, -1, 0, 0};

    void fill(vector<vector<int>>& image, int m, int n, int i, int j, int origin, int color){
        // base case
        if(i == m || i < 0 || j == n || j < 0){
            return;
        }
        if(image[i][j] != origin){
            return;
        }

        // recursive case
        image[i][j] = color;
        for(int k=0;k<4;k++){
            fill(image, m, n, i+dx[k], j+dy[k], origin, color);
        }
    }

    vector<vector<int>> floodFill(vector<vector<int>>& image, int sr, int sc, int color) {

        int m = image.size();
        int n = image[0].size();

        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                if(i == sr && j == sc){
                    fill(image, m, n, i, j, image[i][j], color);
                }
            }
        }

        return image;
    }
};

[03/01/24, 9:54:25 AM] Satvik Saini: int LadderTimeOptimised(int n, int k){
    vector<int> dp(n + 1);

    dp[0] = 1;
    dp[1] = dp[0];

    for (int i = 2; i <= k; i++){
        dp[i] = 2 * dp[i - 1];
    }

    for (int i = k + 1; i <= n; i++){
        dp[i] = 2 * dp[i - 1] - dp[i - k - 1]
    }
    return dp[n];
}

[03/01/24, 1:45:00 PM] Satvik Saini: int LCSTopDown(string s1, string s2, int m, int n, int i, int j, vector<vector<int>> &dp)
{
	// base case
	if (i == m || j == n) {
		return 0;
	}

	// lookup
	if (dp[i][j] != -1) {
		return dp[i][j];
	}

	// recursive case

	// compute the length of the LCS b/w s1[i...m-1] and s2[j...n-1]
	if (s1[i] == s2[j])
	{
		// recursively, compute the length of the LCS b/w s1[i+1...m-1] and s2[j+1...n-1]
		return dp[i][j] = 1 + LCSTopDown(s1, s2, m, n, i + 1, j + 1, dp);
	}

	// recursively, compute the length of the LCS b/w s1[i+1...m-1] and s2[j...n-1]
	int X = LCSTopDown(s1, s2, m, n, i + 1, j, dp);

	// recursively, compute the length of the LCS b/w s1[i...m-1] and s2[j+1...n-1]
	int Y = LCSTopDown(s1, s2, m, n, i, j + 1, dp);

	return dp[i][j] = max(X, Y);
}

[03/01/24, 6:04:04 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    bool isPalindrome(string s){
        int i = 0;
        int j=s.size()-1;

        while(i<j){
            if(s[i] != s[j]) return false;

            i++;
            j--;
        }
        return true;

    }
    string longestPalin(int i, string s){

        // base case

        if(i == s.size()-1)  return string(s[i],1);

        // recursive case

        // you are at the ith index and you need to find the length of longest palindromic substr starting from i 
        string ans = string(s[i],1);
        for(int j = i ; j<s.size() ; j++){
            
            if(isPalindrome(s.substr(i,j-i+1))){
                string x = s.substr(i,j-i+1);
                string y =  longestPalin(j+1,s);
                if(x.size() > y.size()){
                    if(x.size() > ans.size()) ans = x; 
                }
                else{
                    if(y.size() > ans.size()) ans = y;
                }
            }
        }
        // cout<<ans<<" "; 
        return ans;

    }
    string longestPalindrome(string s) {
        return longestPalin(0,s);
    }
};
[03/01/24, 6:04:10 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-palindromic-substring/

[03/01/24, 6:14:23 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: class Solution {
public:
    // whenever we want to avoid the use of loop inside of recursion we try to make recursion do our work for us  
    bool f(string& s1, string& s2,unsigned int i,unsigned  int j, vector<vector<int>>& dp){
        // lookup
        if(dp[i][j] != -1){
            return dp[i][j];
        }
        // base case
        // i 0 -> s1.size() j 0-> s2.size()
        if(i == s1.size()) {
            // if('a'<=s2[j] and s2[j]<='z' || s2[j] == '?') return 0;
            bool flag = true;
            for(unsigned int k = j ; k<s2.size() ; k++){
                if(s2[k] != '*'){
                    flag = false;
                    break;
                }
            }
            return flag;
        }
        if(j == s2.size()) return 0;

        // recursive case

        bool x = false;
        //1. check for alphabet or not 
        if('a'<=s2[j] and s2[j]<='z'){
            if(s1[i] == s2[j]) return f(s1, s2, i+1, j+1, dp);
            return dp[i][j] = false;
        }
        //2.if s2[j] is ?
        if(s2[j]=='?'){
            return dp[i][j] = f(s1, s2, i+1, j+1, dp);
        }
        //3. if s2[j] is * 
        // we can choose no characters
        // we can choose multiple characters 
        return dp[i][j] = f(s1, s2,i+1,j, dp) or  f(s1, s2,i,j+1, dp);
 
    }
    bool isMatch(string s, string p) {
        vector<vector<int>> dp(s.size()+1, vector<int>(p.size()+1, -1));
        return f(s, p, 0, 0, dp);
        
    }
};
