[30/10/24, 4:15:19 PM] Satvik Saini: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

typedef long long ll;

// Define a large number for initialization
const int INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(0);
    
    int N;
    cin >> N;
    
    // Read value array as a string and parse each digit
    string value_str;
    cin >> value_str;
    if(value_str.length() != N){
        // Handle cases where the value line might have spaces
        // Read until we have N digits
        while(value_str.length() < N){
            string temp;
            cin >> temp;
            value_str += temp;
        }
    }
    vector<int> value(N, 0);
    for(int i=0; i<N; ++i){
        if(i < value_str.length() && isdigit(value_str[i])){
            value[i] = value_str[i] - '0';
        }
        else{
            // If not a digit, assign 0 or handle error
            value[i] = 0;
        }
    }
    
    // Read maxQuantity array as a string and parse each digit
    string maxQuantity_str;
    cin >> maxQuantity_str;
    if(maxQuantity_str.length() != N){
        // Read until we have N digits
        while(maxQuantity_str.length() < N){
            string temp;
            cin >> temp;
            maxQuantity_str += temp;
        }
    }
    vector<int> maxQuantity(N, 0);
    for(int i=0; i<N; ++i){
        if(i < maxQuantity_str.length() && isdigit(maxQuantity_str[i])){
            maxQuantity[i] = maxQuantity_str[i] - '0';
        }
        else{
            // If not a digit, assign 0 or handle error
            maxQuantity[i] = 0;
        }
    }
    
    // Read weight array as a string and parse each digit
    string weight_str;
    cin >> weight_str;
    if(weight_str.length() != N){
        // Read until we have N digits
        while(weight_str.length() < N){
            string temp;
            cin >> temp;
            weight_str += temp;
        }
    }
    vector<int> weight(N, 0);
    for(int i=0; i<N; ++i){
        if(i < weight_str.length() && isdigit(weight_str[i])){
            weight[i] = weight_str[i] - '0';
        }
        else{
            // If not a digit, assign 0 or handle error
            weight[i] = 0;
        }
    }
    
    int target;
    cin >> target;
    
    int maxWeight;
    cin >> maxWeight;
    
    // Initialize DP table
    // dp[v][w] = minimum number of blocks to reach value v with weight w
    // Initialize all to INF
    vector<vector<int>> dp(target +1, vector<int>(maxWeight +1, INF));
    dp[0][0] = 0;
    
    for(int i=0; i<N; ++i){
        // Binary representation of maxQuantity[i]
        int qty = maxQuantity[i];
        if(qty ==0){
            continue; // No blocks of this type available
        }
        vector<pair<int, int>> items; // pair of (total_value, total_weight)
        vector<int> counts; // number of blocks in this group
        
        int k =1;
        while(qty >=k){
            items.emplace_back(make_pair(k * value[i], k * weight[i]));
            counts.push_back(k);
            qty -=k;
            k <<=1;
        }
        if(qty >0){
            items.emplace_back(make_pair(qty * value[i], qty * weight[i]));
            counts.push_back(qty);
        }
        
        // For each virtual item
        for(int j=0; j<items.size(); ++j){
            int v = items[j].first;
            int w = items[j].second;
            int cnt = counts[j];
            // Iterate from target down to v
            for(int val = target; val >=v; --val){
                for(int wt = maxWeight; wt >=w; --wt){
                    if(dp[val - v][wt - w] + cnt < dp[val][wt]){
                        dp[val][wt] = dp[val - v][wt - w] + cnt;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    
    // Find the minimum number of blocks among all weights <= maxWeight for target
    int result = INF;
    if(target ==0){
        // Edge case: target=0
        result =0;
    }
    else{
        for(int w=0; w<=maxWeight; ++w){
            if(dp[target][w] < result){
                result = dp[target][w];
            }
        }
    }
    
    if(result != INF){
        cout << result;
    }
    else{
        cout << -1;
    }
}

[30/10/24, 4:15:57 PM] Satvik Saini: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

typedef long long ll;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(0);
    
    int N;
    cin >> N;
    
    vector<long long> arr(N);
    for(int i=0; i<N; ++i){
        cin >> arr[i];
    }
    
    int start, target;
    ll max_steps;
    cin >> start >> target >> max_steps;
    
    // Edge case: start is target
    if(start == target){
        if(max_steps >=0){
            cout << 0;
            return 0;
        }
    }
    
    // Initialize visited array
    vector<bool> visited(N, false);
    
    int current = start;
    ll steps = 0;
    bool found = false;
    
    while(steps < max_steps && !visited[current]){
        if(current == target){
            found = true;
            break;
        }
        visited[current] = true;
        
        // Calculate next position
        ll move = arr[current];
        // To handle negative moves and large moves, compute modulo
        ll next = ((current + (move % N)) % N);
        if(next <0){
            next += N;
        }
        
        current = next;
        steps +=1;
    }
    
    // After loop, check if target was reached
    if(current == target && steps <= max_steps){
        cout << steps;
        return 0;
    }
    
    // It might be possible that in the last step we reached target
    // So check one more time
    if(current == target && steps <= max_steps){
        cout << steps;
        return 0;
    }
    
    // If not found within max_steps
    cout << -1;
}

[31/10/24, 10:07:22 AM] Satvik Saini: In the world of Amazon's vast inventory management, you face a challenge of optimizing two inventories, inv1 and inv2, each containing n elements.

16

17

18

Your goal is to maximize the similarity between these inventories. The similarity is measured by the number of indices (0 <= i < n) where inv1 [i] equals inv2[i].

Amazon provides a unique tool, the "Inventory Optimizer". This tool allows you to perform the following operation:

19

20

21

22

23

Select two distinct indices i and j (where 0 <= i , j < n and i ne j) , provided that the jth element of inv1 is positive.

• Apply the operation: add 1 to inv1[i] and subtract 1 from inv1[j].

Using the Inventory Optimizer, you can perform this operation any number of times (including zero) to maximize the similarity between inv1 and inv2.

Example

n = 3

inv1 = [2, 4, 1]

inv * 2 = [1, 2, 3]

• Apply the operation on indices i = 2 and j = 0,which makes inv1 = [1, 4, 2].

• Next, apply the operation on indices i = 2 and j = 1, which updates inv1 = [1, 3, 3].

D

2

Now, there are two indices, i = 0 and i = 2 for which inv1[i] = inv2[i]. Since it's impossible to make the elements at all indices of the two arrays equal, the answer is 2.

Function Description

Complete the function getMaxEquallndices in the editor below.

getMaxEquallndices has the following

parameters:

int inv1 [n]: an array of integers

int inv2[n]: an array of integers

Returns

int: maximum similarity of the two inventories inv1, inv2 after the operations.

Constraints

• 1 <= n <= 10 ^ 5

• 1 <= inv * 1[i], inv * 2[i] <= 10 ^ 4
▼Input Format For Custom Testing

The first line contains an integer, n, denoting the number of elements in inv1.

The next line contains an integer, n, denoting the number of elements in inv2.

Each line i of the in subsequent lines contains inv2[i] describing the array inv2.

[31/10/24, 10:09:31 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: In the world of Amazon's vast inventory management, you face a challenge of optimizing two inventories, inv1 and inv2, each containing n elements.

Your goal is to maximize the similarity between these inventories. The similarity is measured by the number of indices (0 <= i < n) where inv1 [i] equals inv2[i].

Amazon provides a unique tool, the "Inventory Optimizer". This tool allows you to perform the following operation:
Select two distinct indices i and j (where 0 <= i , j < n and i ne j) , provided that the jth element of inv1 is positive.

• Apply the operation: add 1 to inv1[i] and subtract 1 from inv1[j].

Using the Inventory Optimizer, you can perform this operation any number of times (including zero) to maximize the similarity between inv1 and inv2.

Example

n = 3

inv1 = [2, 4, 1]

inv * 2 = [1, 2, 3]

• Apply the operation on indices i = 2 and j = 0,which makes inv1 = [1, 4, 2].

• Next, apply the operation on indices i = 2 and j = 1, which updates inv1 = [1, 3, 3].


Now, there are two indices, i = 0 and i = 2 for which inv1[i] = inv2[i]. Since it's impossible to make the elements at all indices of the two arrays equal, the answer is 2.

Function Description

Complete the function getMaxEquallndices in the editor below.

getMaxEquallndices has the following

parameters:

int inv1 [n]: an array of integers

int inv2[n]: an array of integers

Returns

int: maximum similarity of the two inventories inv1, inv2 after the operations.

Constraints

• 1 <= n <= 10 ^ 5

• 1 <= inv * 1[i], inv * 2[i] <= 10 ^ 4
▼Input Format For Custom Testing

The first line contains an integer, n, denoting the number of elements in inv1.

Each line / of the n subsequent lines contains inv1 [i] describing the array inv1.

The next line contains an integer, n, denoting the number of elements in inv2.

Each line i of the in subsequent lines contains inv2[i] describing the array inv2.
code in cpp
[31/10/24, 10:11:20 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int getMaxEquallndices(vector<int> inv1, vector<int> inv2) {
    const int OFFSET = 10000;
    vector<int> freq(20001, 0);
    int n = inv1.size();
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        int d = inv2[i] - inv1[i];
        freq[d + OFFSET]++;
    }

    int k = freq[0 + OFFSET];

    for(int x=1; x<=10000; x++){
        int pos = x + OFFSET;
        int neg = -x + OFFSET;
        if(neg >=0 && neg < 20001){
            k += 2 * min(freq[pos], freq[neg]);
        }
    }
    return k;
}

// Example usage:
int main(){
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> inv1(n);
    for(int &x: inv1) cin >> x;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> inv2(n);
    for(int &x: inv2) cin >> x;
    cout << getMaxEquallndices(inv1, inv2);
} ‎<This message was edited>
[31/10/24, 10:12:42 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int getMaxEquallndices(vector<int> inv1, vector<int> inv2) {
    const int OFFSET = 10000;
    vector<int> freq(20001, 0);
    int n = inv1.size();
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int d = inv2[i] - inv1[i];
        freq[d + OFFSET]++;
    }
    int k = freq[0 + OFFSET];
    for(int x = 1; x <= 10000; x++) {
        int pos = x + OFFSET;
        int neg = -x + OFFSET;
        if(neg >= 0 && neg < 20001){
            k += 2 * min(freq[pos], freq[neg]);
        }
    }
    return k;
}

int main(){
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> inv1(n);
    for(int &x: inv1) cin >> x;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> inv2(n);
    for(int &x: inv2) cin >> x;
    cout << getMaxEquallndices(inv1, inv2);
}

[31/10/24, 10:16:00 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int getMaxEquallndices(vector<int> inv1, vector<int> inv2) {
    // Calculate the total sum of inv1
    long long sum_inv1 = 0;
    for(auto &x: inv1) sum_inv1 += x;
    
    // Sort inv2 in non-decreasing order
    sort(inv2.begin(), inv2.end());
    
    // Compute prefix sums of sorted inv2
    int n = inv2.size();
    vector<long long> prefix(n + 1, 0);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        prefix[i + 1] = prefix[i] + (long long)inv2[i];
    }
    
    // Binary search to find the maximum k where prefix[k] <= sum_inv1
    int left = 0, right = n;
    int ans = 0;
    while(left <= right){
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
        if(prefix[mid] <= sum_inv1){
            ans = mid;
            left = mid + 1;
        }
        else{
            right = mid - 1;
        }
    }
    
    return ans;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(0);
    
    int n1;
    cin >> n1;
    vector<int> inv1(n1);
    for(int &x: inv1) cin >> x;
    
    int n2;
    cin >> n2;
    // It's given that both inventories have the same size
    // But to ensure correctness, you can handle cases where n1 != n2
    // For this problem, assuming n1 == n2
    vector<int> inv2(n2);
    for(int &x: inv2) cin >> x;
    
    cout << getMaxEquallndices(inv1, inv2);
}
[31/10/24, 10:16:52 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int getMaxEquallndices(vector<int> inv1, vector<int> inv2) {
    long long sum_inv1 = accumulate(inv1.begin(), inv1.end(), 0LL);
    sort(inv2.begin(), inv2.end());
    int n = inv2.size();
    vector<long long> prefix(n + 1, 0);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        prefix[i + 1] = prefix[i] + (long long)inv2[i];
    }
    int left = 0, right = n;
    int ans = 0;
    while(left <= right){
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
        if(prefix[mid] <= sum_inv1){
            ans = mid;
            left = mid + 1;
        }
        else{
            right = mid - 1;
        }
    }
    return ans;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(0);
    int n1;
    cin >> n1;
    vector<int> inv1(n1);
    for(int &x: inv1) cin >> x;
    int n2;
    cin >> n2;
    vector<int> inv2(n2);
    for(int &x: inv2) cin >> x;
    cout << getMaxEquallndices(inv1, inv2);
}

[31/10/24, 10:21:15 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int getMaxEquallndices(vector<int> inv1, vector<int> inv2) {
    long long sum_inv1 = accumulate(inv1.begin(), inv1.end(), 0LL);
    sort(inv2.begin(), inv2.end());
    int n = inv2.size();
    long long current_sum = 0;
    int k = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if(current_sum + inv2[i] <= sum_inv1){
            current_sum += inv2[i];
            k++;
        }
        else{
            break;
        }
    }
    return k;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(0);
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> inv1(n);
    for(int &x: inv1) cin >> x;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> inv2(n);
    for(int &x: inv2) cin >> x;
    cout << getMaxEquallndices(inv1, inv2);
}
[31/10/24, 10:25:11 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int getMaxEquallndices(vector<int> inv1, vector<int> inv2) {
    long long sum_inv1 = accumulate(inv1.begin(), inv1.end(), 0LL);
    sort(inv2.begin(), inv2.end());
    int n = inv2.size();
    vector<long long> prefix(n + 1, 0);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        prefix[i + 1] = prefix[i] + (long long)inv2[i];
    }
    int left = 0, right = n;
    int ans = 0;
    while(left <= right){
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
        if(prefix[mid] <= sum_inv1 && (mid < n || (mid == n && prefix[mid] == sum_inv1))){
            ans = mid;
            left = mid + 1;
        }
        else{
            right = mid - 1;
        }
    }
    return ans;
}

    for(int &x: inv1) cin >> x;
    int n2;
    cin >> n2;
    vector<int> inv2(n2);
    for(int &x: inv2) cin >> x;
    cout << getMaxEquallndices(inv1, inv2);
}

[03/11/24, 10:19:44 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: There is a puzzle using a rectangular grid. The upper left corner is at (row, column) = (0,0). Each cell contains an integer. The score starts at 0 and is the sum of all the integers in each cell visited as the grid is  traversed. Movement begins in either the top or the bottom row and stays within the bounds of the grid. Only 1 cell can be visited per row per direction. Determine the maximum achievable score



Movement for the two scenarios are as C thefollows:

1. From a a cell (i, j) = (0, p) i.e. in the top row

(i + 1, j - 1)

(i + 1, j)

(i + 1, j + 1) 

2. From a cell (i,j) = (rows-1,q), i.e. in the bottom row:

(i - 1, j - 1)

(i - 1, j)

(i - 1, j + 1) ‎<This message was edited>

[03/11/24, 10:22:17 AM] Satvik Saini: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

typedef long long ll;

// Function to compute the maximum sum starting from top or bottom
int getMaxSum(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int R, int C) {
    // Top-Down DP
    // Initialize previous row's DP with the first row of the grid
    vector<int> prev_top(C, 0);
    for(int j = 0; j < C; ++j){
        prev_top[j] = grid[0][j];
    }

    // Variable to store the maximum sum for top-down traversal
    int max_top = INT32_MIN;

    // Iterate from the second row to the last row
    for(int i = 1; i < R; ++i){
        vector<int> current(C, 0);
        for(int j = 0; j < C; ++j){
            int best_prev = INT32_MIN;
            // Check the three possible cells from the previous row
            for(int dj = -1; dj <=1; ++dj){
                int prev_j = j + dj;
                if(prev_j >=0 && prev_j < C){
                    best_prev = max(best_prev, prev_top[prev_j]);
                }
            }
            current[j] = grid[i][j] + best_prev;
        }
        prev_top = current;
    }

    // After top-down traversal, find the maximum sum in the last row
    for(int j = 0; j < C; ++j){
        max_top = max(max_top, prev_top[j]);
    }

    // Bottom-Up DP
    // Initialize previous row's DP with the last row of the grid
    vector<int> prev_bottom(C, 0);
    for(int j = 0; j < C; ++j){
        prev_bottom[j] = grid[R-1][j];
    }

    // Variable to store the maximum sum for bottom-up traversal
    int max_bottom = INT32_MIN;

    // Iterate from the second last row to the first row
    for(int i = R-2; i >=0; --i){
        vector<int> current(C, 0);
        for(int j = 0; j < C; ++j){
            int best_prev = INT32_MIN;
            // Check the three possible cells from the next row
            for(int dj = -1; dj <=1; ++dj){
                int prev_j = j + dj;
                if(prev_j >=0 && prev_j < C){
                    best_prev = max(best_prev, prev_bottom[prev_j]);
                }
            }
            current[j] = grid[i][j] + best_prev;
        }
        prev_bottom = current;
    }

    // After bottom-up traversal, find the maximum sum in the first row
    for(int j = 0; j < C; ++j){
        max_bottom = max(max_bottom, prev_bottom[j]);
    }

    // The final answer is the maximum of top-down and bottom-up traversals
    return max(max_top, max_bottom);
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(0);

    int R, C;
    cin >> R >> C;

    // Read the grid
    vector<vector<int>> grid(R, vector<int>(C, 0));
    for(int i =0; i < R; ++i){
        for(int j =0; j < C; ++j){
            cin >> grid[i][j];
        }
    }

    // Compute the maximum sum
    int result = getMaxSum(grid, R, C);

    // Output the result
    cout << result << "\n";

    return 0;
}

using namespace std;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(0);
    int m, n;
    cin >> m >> n;
    vector<vector<int>> grid(m, vector<int>(n));
    for(int i=0; i<m; ++i){
        for(int j=0; j<n; ++j){
            cin >> grid[i][j];
        }
    }
    vector<int> dp_prev(n, 0);
    for(int j=0; j<n; ++j){
        dp_prev[j] = grid[0][j];
    }
    for(int i=1; i<m; ++i){
        vector<int> dp_curr(n, 0);
        for(int j=0; j<n; ++j){
            int max_val = dp_prev[j];
            if(j >0){
                max_val = max(max_val, dp_prev[j-1]);
            }
            if(j <n-1){
                max_val = max(max_val, dp_prev[j+1]);
            }
            dp_curr[j] = max_val + grid[i][j];
        }
        dp_prev = dp_curr;
    }
    int max_top = *max_element(dp_prev.begin(), dp_prev.end());
    dp_prev.assign(n, 0);
    for(int j=0; j<n; ++j){
        dp_prev[j] = grid[m-1][j];
    }
    for(int i=m-2; i>=0; --i){
        vector<int> dp_curr(n, 0);
        for(int j=0; j<n; ++j){
            int max_val = dp_prev[j];
            if(j >0){
                max_val = max(max_val, dp_prev[j-1]);
            }
            if(j <n-1){
                max_val = max(max_val, dp_prev[j+1]);
            }
            dp_curr[j] = max_val + grid[i][j];
        }
        dp_prev = dp_curr;
    }
    int max_bottom = *max_element(dp_prev.begin(), dp_prev.end());
    cout << max(max_top, max_bottom) << "\n";
}

[03/11/24, 10:46:03 AM] Satvik Saini: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int getMaxScoreTopToBottom(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int start_col) {
    int m = grid.size();
    int n = grid[0].size();
    vector<vector<int>> dp(m, vector<int>(n, INT_MIN));
    dp[0][start_col] = grid[0][start_col];

    for (int i = 1; i < m; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
            int max_val = INT_MIN;
            if (j > 0) max_val = max(max_val, dp[i - 1][j - 1]);
            max_val = max(max_val, dp[i - 1][j]);
            if (j < n - 1) max_val = max(max_val, dp[i - 1][j + 1]);
            if (max_val != INT_MIN) dp[i][j] = max_val + grid[i][j];
        }
    }

    return *max_element(dp[m - 1].begin(), dp[m - 1].end());
}

int getMaxScoreBottomToTop(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int start_col) {
    int m = grid.size();
    int n = grid[0].size();
    vector<vector<int>> dp(m, vector<int>(n, INT_MIN));
    dp[m - 1][start_col] = grid[m - 1][start_col];

    for (int i = m - 2; i >= 0; --i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
            int max_val = INT_MIN;
            if (j > 0) max_val = max(max_val, dp[i + 1][j - 1]);
            max_val = max(max_val, dp[i + 1][j]);
            if (j < n - 1) max_val = max(max_val, dp[i + 1][j + 1]);
            if (max_val != INT_MIN) dp[i][j] = max_val + grid[i][j];
        }
    }

    return *max_element(dp[0].begin(), dp[0].end());
}

int main() {
    int m, n;
    cin >> m >> n;
    vector<vector<int>> grid(m, vector<int>(n));
    for (int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
            cin >> grid[i][j];
        }
    }

    int p, q;
    cin >> p >> q;

    int max_top = getMaxScoreTopToBottom(grid, p);
    int max_bottom = getMaxScoreBottomToTop(grid, q);

    cout << max(max_top, max_bottom) << "\n";
}

[22/11/24, 7:25:04 PM] Satvik Saini: #include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <sstream>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <string>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

void count_requests(const string& filename) {
    // Open the log file
    ifstream infile(filename);
    if (!infile) {
        cerr << "Error opening file!" << endl;
        return;
    }

    // Map to store the count of requests for each hostname
    unordered_map<string, int> host_count;

    string line;
    
    // Read each line from the file
    while (getline(infile, line)) {
        // Find the first space which separates the hostname from the rest of the log record
        stringstream ss(line);
        string hostname;
        ss >> hostname;  // Extract the hostname
        
        // Increment the count for this hostname
        if (hostname != "-") {
            host_count[hostname]++;
        }
    }

    // Create the output file name
    string output_filename = "records_" + filename;

    // Open the output file
    ofstream outfile(output_filename);
    if (!outfile) {
        cerr << "Error opening output file!" << endl;
        return;
    }

    // Write the hostnames and their corresponding request counts to the output file
    for (const auto& entry : host_count) {
        outfile << entry.first << " " << entry.second << endl;
    }

    cout << "Results have been written to " << output_filename << endl;
}

int main() {
    // Read the input filename from standard input
    string filename;
    cin >> filename;

    // Call the function to process the log file
    count_requests(filename);

    return 0;
}

[05/12/24, 10:05:11 AM] Satvik Saini: John and Luke are playing a game. John gives Luke a set of cards with distinct words written on each card. John can ask Luke questions from any of the following

categories:

Question 1: What is the lexicographically largest word?

Question 2: What is the lexicographically smallest word?

Question 3: What is the lexicographically second smallest word?

Question 4: What is the lexicographically second largest word?

Question 5: What is the lexicographically smallest word with its letters in the reverse order? Update this word on the respective card.

Write an algorithm to help Luke answer all the questions John asks.

Input

The first line of the input consists of an integer N, representing the number of cards. The second line consists of N space-separated strings representing the word written on each card.

The third line consists of an integer Q, representing the number of questions.

The last line consists of Q space-separated integers representing the questions asked.

Output

Print a list of strings representing the answer to each question asked.

Constraints

2≤ N ≤ 104

1s len ≤ 102; where len is the length of a word

15 Q≤ 105

Example

Input

3

abc cde fgh

3

125

A

Output

fgh abc cba
Explanation:

The output of the first query to identify the lexicographically largest word is 'fgh.'

The output of the second query to identify the lexicographically smallest word is 'abc.' The output of the third query to identify the lexicographically smallest word with its letters in the reverse order is 'cba. After this, the word 'cba' is updated on the card also.

Code in java

[06/12/24, 11:20:14 AM] Satvik Saini: #include <iostream>
using namespace std;

string solution(int M, int R, int D) {
    // If the total days are less than the required sales, it's impossible.
    if (R > D) {
        return "NO";
    }

    // Calculate the maximum number of units that can be sold in D days
    int maxSellable = min(D, M + D);

    // If the required units R are less than or equal to maxSellable, it's possible
    if (R <= maxSellable) {
        return "YES";
    } else {
        return "NO";
    }
}

int main() {
    int M, R, D;
    cin >> M >> R >> D;
    cout << solution(M, R, D) << endl;
    return 0;
}
[06/12/24, 11:20:35 AM] Tanmay DTU CB: #include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void solution(long long M, long long R, long long D) {
    // Case 1: If R > D, it's impossible to sell R items in D days
    if (R > D) {
        cout << "NO" << endl;
        return;
    }

    // Case 2: If storage capacity M >= R, we can sell R items without restocking
    if (M >= R) {
        cout << "YES" << endl;
        return;
    }

    // Case 3: Calculate if restocking can be done within the given days
    // Number of items that need to be restocked
    long long items_to_restock = R - M;

    // Each restock allows selling M items. Calculate restock days required.
    long long restock_days = (items_to_restock + M - 1) / M; // Equivalent to ceil(items_to_restock / M)

    // Total days required is restock days + the R days of selling
    long long total_days_required = M + restock_days;

    if (total_days_required <= D) {
        cout << "YES" << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "NO" << endl;
    }
}

int main() {
    long long M, R, D;
    cin >> M >> R >> D;
    solution(M, R, D);
    return 0;
}

[06/12/24, 5:45:44 PM] Tanmay DTU CB: Frontend Intern Assignment
Masterlist Management System Role Overview
As a frontend developer, you will implement the user interface and interaction layer of our Masterlist Management System. Your task is to translate product requirements into an intuitive, efficient, and robust web application using React.js.
Note
This is a collaborative assignment round. There are no right answers, only figuring out your way to the outcome. We are interested in the process.
Masterlist
A Masterlist in an ERP system is like a big, organized address book for all the important stuff your business needs to keep track of. It’s a central place where key information—like details about products, customers, suppliers, or employees—is stored.
There are different types of masters– product master, customer master, supplier master, inventory master,etc. This assignment is solely for the product related master.
Problem Statement
The current masterlist setup process faces critical challenges:
1. Manual and Time-Consuming Process
2. Error-Prone Workflow
3. Poor User Experience
Current workflow issues:
● Heavily manual data conversion (Google Sheets to CSV to JSON)
● Reliance on technical tools like Postman
● Delayed validation feedback
● Data mismatches disrupting downstream processes
● Lack of real-time validation
 ● Complex interdependencies
● Poor user guidance
● Limited visibility into incomplete items
Assignment Objective
Develop a React-based web application that:
● Automates masterlist data management
● Provides real-time data validation
● Offers an intuitive, user-friendly interface
● Simplifies bulk upload procedure
● Simplifies error handling
Technical Requirements
1. Application Structure Create a React application with sections for a. Items
b. Bill of Materials (BOM) 2. State Management
a. Ensure real-time synchronization across tabs
3. File Handling Capabilities
a. CSV upload and download
b. Template generation
c. Comprehensive error reporting
d. Support for bulk data operations
4. User Interface Requirements
a. b. c.
Responsive design
Intuitive navigation
Clear, actionable error messaging
Specific Section Requirements
Item Master
Mandatory Fields:
● internal_item_name
● Type {enum} (sell/purchase/component)
● UoM {enum} (kgs/nos)

 ● Avg_weight_needed bool
● UoM
● Scrap_type for type = Sell
System Generated Fields:
● Created_by ● Tenant_id ● Id
● createdAt
● updatedAt
Key Validations:
● Unique internal_item_name + tenant combination
● Non-null scrap_type for items having type = sell
● Min buffer not Null for Sell and Purchase
● Max buffer >= Min Buffer
● If Max buffer = Null or min buffer = NULL , take default as 0
Note - Refer API Endpoints Example Calls, all non-mentioned fields are not mandatory.
Bill of Materials
Section Mandatory Fields:
● Item ID
● Component ID
● Quantity
System Generated Fields:
● Id
● Created_by
● Last_updated_by ● createdAt
● updatedAt
Validation Constraints:
● Sell items should have atleast 1 entry as item_id, if no data entered then display in the pending tab section as pending job.

● Purchase items should have atleast 1 entry as component_id, if no data entered then display in the pending tab section as pending job.
● Component items: atleast one entry as item_id and one as component_id required,
● BoM cannot be created for items not created yet.
● Sell item cannot be a component in BoM
● Purchase item cannot be item_id in BOM
● Item id + component id should be unique.
● Quantity should be between 1 to 100
Error Handling
For datasets with errors, Upload and create the correct ones.
Give a downloadable error file (only incorrect entries) with a column explaining the issue Display the number of correct entries uploaded and Pending data to be uploaded.
● Option to download and rectify csv file for incorrect entries(Mandatory)
● Help track and rectify errors in the system(Good to have)
Evaluation Criteria
1. Code Quality (20%)
2. Feature Completeness (60%) (Priority)
3. User Experience (20%)
4. Extra Credit (10%) (attempt only when above features are completed)
a. New Feature implemented (unleash your creativity)
Acceptance Criteria
● Error Handling should be working.
● All validations should be implemented.
● CSV parsing and validation for Bulk Upload should be working
● UX should be easy to use and understandable with necessary pop-ups, errors, nudges,
data display, confirmations
